commit 98a92f4257b9fb11e5b624511755c377ef7d104b
Author: claude (dev43 c61bd391-348a-41f6-a84d-800d0827c716) <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Fri Jul 3 12:39:28 2026 -0400

    git review driver: idiomatic guards, fail-on-undecodable Unicode, style cleanup

    Harden and tidy git-review-driver.sh (shared core of git-meld / git-kdiff3 /
    git-diff-review):

    - Required-var asserts use the same '[ -n ... ] || { printf; exit 2; }' guard
      idiom as the neighbouring display_regular_file check, dropping the ':' null
      command (R-130) and the '${var:?}' form.
    - Undecodable/non-UTF-8 Unicode (unicode-show rc 2) in a blob OR a path is now
      FATAL: it is recorded in a global flag and every non-error exit routes through
      git_review_finish(), which exits non-zero (git then aborts the diff) so an
      undecodable payload cannot pass as a clean review. Decodable non-ASCII (rc 1)
      stays warn-only. GIT_REVIEW_UNICODE_NONFATAL=<non-empty> downgrades the hard
      abort ONLY when the re-dispatch block's shared status file exists to defer to:
      the finding is recorded there and the run still exits non-zero at the very end,
      after showing every file. With no status file (e.g. the driver wired directly
      as git's diff.external, bypassing re-dispatch) it fails closed immediately
      rather than let git see a clean external diff.
    - git_review_unicode_rc is a global (not a local) so the last scan's exit code
      is readable by callers.
    - The '>= 3' recursion guard now prints a useful error before 'exit 255'.
    - Style: one assignment per line (no ';' chaining, R-074); multi-line function
      bodies (is_submodule_blob, extract_commit, read_target); case arm reflowed
      (R-070/R-071); interpolated values single-quoted in messages (R-024). Tested
      '--' end-of-options support: unicode-show has no option parsing and awk does
      not accept it in the file position, so no new '--' was added.

    Path tab/newline check (addresses an AI-review finding): unicode-show -- like
    stcat and grep-find-unicode-wrapper, whose sources all allow '\t'/'\n' via the
    '[\x1b\n\t\x20-\x7E]' allow-list -- never flags a tab or newline, yet in a PATH
    those bytes are anomalous and can forge/hide diff-output lines. Rather than
    reimplement a Unicode scanner, everything else (non-ASCII, bidi, CR, NUL,
    non-UTF-8) stays delegated to unicode-show; a single 'case' adds only the two
    bytes it deliberately allows. (NUL cannot occur in a path: argv is
    NUL-terminated.) Verified: all three tools allow tab/newline; the case matches
    tab/newline only (CR already caught by unicode-show).

    Also fold in pre-existing correctness fixes surfaced by AI review of this diff:

    - Deletion Unicode-scan gap: a deletion hands new_file=/dev/null, so scanning
      only the new side never inspected a removed file's content. Fall back to the
      old side (mirrors the binary check), so removed Trojan-Source / undecodable
      content is still surfaced (and now fatal).
    - '.gitattributes' warning could be dropped: piping 'git diff --name-only'
      straight into grep let a git failure mask a real match under pipefail. Capture
      the name list first, then grep, so git's rc cannot suppress the warning.
    - Symlink add/delete mislabel: the absent (/dev/null) side printed
      '(regular file)' instead of '(none)', contradicting the never-misleading
      invariant. Label it '(none)' when the side is absent.
    - NONFATAL status-file write is no longer swallowed with '|| true': a write
      error now fails hard, so a fatal finding cannot silently pass as clean.

    Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 <noreply@anthropic.com>
    Claude-Session: https://claude.ai/code/session_01XmRjrQxBBbQE6eyjWnvzjb

