    entries with a comment pointing back at the matching commented
    block in the script.

commit 85c2faf012a8de5bfbc994f06cd637740bd9d36a
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Wed May 27 11:27:00 2026 +0000

    dm-github-org-policy: GitHub-App-only hint for PAT endpoints; order-preserving audit test

    PAT-endpoint hints
    ==================
    The two endpoints under 'fine-grained PAT activity':

      GET /orgs/{org}/personal-access-token-requests
      GET /orgs/{org}/personal-access-tokens

    are GitHub-App-only per docs.github.com:

      "Only GitHub Apps can use this endpoint."

    A classic PAT with admin:org gets HTTP 404 with an empty
    'x-accepted-oauth-scopes' response header (no OAuth scope grants
    access). A fine-grained PAT gets the same. The org's
    PAT-restriction policy toggle does NOT change this - it controls
    whether PATs may be USED to access org resources, not whether a
    REST client can ENUMERATE such tokens.

    Prior hint text claimed 'token may lack admin:org / PAT
    restriction policy not enforced', which sent operators chasing
    fixes that cannot resolve the 404 under PAT auth. Replace with
    '(endpoint accepts GitHub App tokens only, not PATs)' and add a
    block comment near the call sites documenting why.

    Order-preserving audit test
    ===========================
    ci/tests/test_dm_audit.sh used substring-only assertions. A
    silent section reorder (e.g. PAT activity printed before
    code-security defaults) would pass: every substring is still
    present in the output. That kind of regression is invisible to
    substring matches but does change the meaning a maintainer reads
    off the report.

    Replace the per-needle 'grep --fixed-strings' loop with a
    one-pass walker that advances through required[] monotonically:
    required[i] must appear at or after the line where required[i-1]
    matched. Missing-entirely and out-of-order failures are reported
    separately so the diagnostic points at the right thing.

    Adversarial verified locally:
    - Replace one needle with a string the script never emits ->
      'FAIL: missing expected fragment: <needle>' (existing semantic).
    - Swap two needles in required[] -> 'FAIL: out-of-order
      fragment: <needle>' on each cascade entry (new semantic).

