    ghorg_parse_rate_limit_wait: signal 'no signal' via exit code, not empty stdout

    Replace the magic empty-string sentinel with standard shell idiom:
    value on stdout, success/failure via exit code. The caller switches
    from 'wait="$(...)"; if [ -z "${wait}" ]; then ...' to
    'if ! wait="$(ghorg_parse_rate_limit_wait "${hdr_file}")"; then
      wait="$(ghorg_compute_backoff_seconds "${attempt}")"; fi',
    which documents itself at the call site and removes the body-comment
    warning about not echoing '0'.

