    Per the StackOverflow research the FIXME pointed at: GitHub's POST
    /repos/{src}/{src_repo}/forks returns 202 (accepted), and the newly
    created repo only becomes API-visible some seconds later. Querying
    GET /repos/{owner}/{repo} can return 404 during that window; once it
    returns 200, the repo exists but may still be empty - subsequent
    PATCH /repos, PUT .../actions/permissions, and POST .../merge-upstream
    calls can hit 409/422 against the empty-repo state.

    Add a wait_for_fork_ready helper that polls
    GET /repos/{owner}/{repo}/commits?per_page=1 with exponential backoff
    (1, 2, 4, 8, 16, 30s cap) until 200, bounded by
    GHORG_FORK_READY_TIMEOUT_SECONDS (default 300s / 5 min). The call site
    runs the wait once per newly-POSTed fork before the existing list +
    configure flow. On timeout, the helper warns and returns non-zero;
    the caller's || true keeps the batch moving and the next idempotent
    run picks up the configure.

    Skipped under GHORG_MOCK=1 so the existing mock-API test fixtures
    don't have to ship a /commits fixture for every forked repo.

