commit e9c39ed31caa285b89e85739d718944684540824
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Mon May 18 15:00:36 2026 +0000

    github-org-fork / ghorg_account_type: include response body in warn lines

    When a non-success status comes back, the operator usually wants to
    see GitHub's error body to understand whether the cause was scope,
    quota, validation, or a hostile name collision. Add a bounded
    '${response_body:0:512}' tail to every existing warn/error in the
    configure_one PATCH and PUT paths, the sync_one 409/422/* arms, and
    the ghorg_account_type non-200 path. The 512-byte cap protects the
    log line; the log helper still routes the value through
    sanitize-string for terminal safety.

commit 60131538460bff2a1f01bce1d8b6a488f4aa15df
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Mon May 18 14:58:44 2026 +0000

    sync-branches 422 message + github-org-push branch-exists pre-check

    - github-org-fork sync_one: HTTP 422 from POST .../merge-upstream
      means 'validation failed', which covers more than 'branch missing'
      (target isn't a fork, target isn't behind, etc.). Don't claim a
      specific cause; let the operator inspect.
    - github-org-push: verify the local branch exists with
      'git rev-parse --verify' before constructing the refspec, so a
      missing branch produces a clear skip instead of a confusing
      'src refspec ... does not match any' lost inside the generic push
      warn line.

commit c3335558b3817747c62d828a42d7c3829f9da5c5
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Mon May 18 14:58:00 2026 +0000

    ghorg_api: clarify retry-attempt zero-indexing isn't a 0-second wait

    The earlier FIXME assumed the formula was linear (30 * attempt). The
    actual formula in ghorg_compute_backoff_seconds is exponential
    (30 * (1 << attempt)), so attempt=0 yields a 30s wait, not 0s. The
    behaviour already waits before every retry; replace the FIXME with a
    short note about the math so the next reader doesn't re-derive.

commit 57036f4e06c24face592ee6f4f8ad7458bcacb2f
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Mon May 18 14:57:37 2026 +0000

    ghorg_api: validate HTTP_STATUS sentinel; detect 403 rate-limit via headers

    - Require the 'HTTP_STATUS:' prefix curl appends via --write-out
      before treating the last line as the status. If the prefix is
      missing (curl wrote nothing, or the caller passed only the body),
      fail closed instead of silently consuming the last body line as a
      status code.
    - ghorg_status_of: same prefix gate so out-of-band consumers can't
      mis-parse the result either.
    - Replace the 403 body-grep heuristic with header inspection:
      - 'x-ratelimit-remaining: 0' signals the primary rate limit;
      - 'retry-after:' signals the secondary rate limit.
      Both are documented in the GitHub REST rate-limits docs; the body
      wording ('rate limit' / 'secondary rate') is not contractual.

commit b74ccdf2b91f86d2b3deb48852369d8ebad5d1dd
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Mon May 18 14:56:16 2026 +0000

    ghorg_validate_name: add 'ref' kind; refuse unknown kinds outright

    - New 'ref' kind: allowlist '^[A-Za-z0-9._/-]+$' so 'feature/foo' is
      accepted, length cap GHORG_MAX_BRANCH_NAME_LEN=255 (filesystem max
      for refs stored under .git/refs/), additional rejection of leading
      '/' and '//' substrings. Deeper format checks stay where they
      already are: 'git check-ref-format refs/heads/...' downstream.
    - Default 'kind' branch in the case now errors out instead of silently
      reusing the repo cap (audited: every existing caller passes 'user',
      'repo', or now 'ref').
    - github-org-push: branch validation switched from 'repo' to 'ref', so
      feature/foo branches no longer get a misleading 'over cap' message.
    - Property fuzz test (test_fuzz_validate_name.sh) now rotates over
      all three kinds; the divergence oracle is kept in lockstep.
    - Targeted attacks test (test_validate_name_rejects_attacks.sh)
      gains coverage of: good refs (master, feature/foo, claude/foo-bar,
      release/1.2.3, .hidden-branch), bad refs (leading '/', '//' double
      slash, '@{1}', etc.), ref 255-char OK / 256-char reject, and the
      unknown-kind reject path.

