commit 00fb54e3800c71be516f1d119e170f3733ab84e3
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Sun May 17 16:12:26 2026 +0000

    pkg_need_version_bump_show: filter reprepro list to source line, drop sort

    Two issues with the previous one-liner extracting reprepro_version:

      reprepro_version="$(printf '%s\n' "${repo_query_output}" \
          | awk 'NF{print $NF}' | sort -V | tail -n1)"

    1. sort -V follows GNU "version sort" rules, NOT Debian version
       semantics. Epochs (`1:1.0` vs `0:2.0`), tildes (`1.0~rc1` < `1.0`),
       and a few other Debian-specific orderings can be sorted wrong.
       The right Debian-version comparator is `dpkg --compare-versions`.

    2. The pipeline took the highest of all per-architecture lines.
       reprepro tracks at most ONE version per source-package per
       codename, so every architecture line carries the same version;
       sorting was a workaround for using the wrong data source.

    Filter to the `|source:` line instead - that's the canonical per-
    package entry. No sort needed. Multi-step for readability:

      1. query reprepro
      2. grep '|source:' to pick the canonical line
      3. awk '{print $NF}' to extract the version

    Empty result still means "package absent" / "needs build", which
    the downstream comparison handles unchanged.

