commit afbc4a16421b75ed1664a231c705ccdc132f56ce
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Sun May 17 09:09:08 2026 +0000

    pkg_need_version_bump_show: detect interrupted builds via reprepro version

    Replace the unreliable "last commit is 'bumped changelog version'"
    sentinel with a comparison between debian/changelog and the version
    actually published in the local reprepro repo.

    The old sentinel had a real failure mode: if a previous batch ran
    the bump commit and built the .deb but was interrupted (Ctrl-C,
    OOM, disk-full, sudo timeout) before reprepro-add finished, the
    changelog moved ahead of reprepro yet subsequent runs would see
    the bump commit and skip forever. The mismatch surfaced only when
    a downstream consumer noticed the apt repository was stale.

    New logic queries dm-reprepro-wrapper (which self-sources
    help-steps/variables and handles basedir/dbdir options) for the
    package's current local-codename version and compares it via
    `dpkg --compare-versions`:

      - changelog == reprepro and last commit IS the bump: truly done,
        skip (unless batch_meta_force_version_bump=y)
      - changelog == reprepro and last commit is something else: new
        work since the bump, fall through
      - changelog > reprepro: interrupted previous build, fall through
        (pkg_upstream_and_debian_changelog_bump now no-ops via a new
        guard so we don't re-bump unnecessarily)
      - changelog < reprepro: rare; warn and continue, let reprepro-add
        surface the mismatch loudly
      - package absent from repo: first build, fall through

    The rest of the pipeline (sign tags, push, deb-pkg,
    reprepro-remove/add) is already idempotent so a resumed build
    runs cleanly to completion.

