commit 1db0b4a9c2414e2cc6ba3328bc68d2484221f60b
Author: assisted-by-ai (Bot Account) <228987186+assisted-by-ai@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Sat May 16 04:45:49 2026 -0400

    ci(apt-cache): cp --update=none replaces deprecated --no-clobber

    Live kloak rerun (https://github.com/org-ai-assisted/kloak/actions/runs/25935205795/attempts/2)
    of the merged apt-install-with-cache composite action emits:

      cp: warning: behavior of -n is non-portable and may change in
      future; use --update=none instead

    GNU coreutils 9.x deprecates the -n / --no-clobber short-flag
    semantics. The newer --update=none is the documented replacement
    and is supported on coreutils >= 9.1; Ubuntu 24.04 ships 9.4, and
    all callers (reusable-cppcheck/bandit/coverity, msgcollector\'s
    local-*-tests.yml, security-misc\'s local-dbus-fuzz.yml +
    local-python-lint.yml) run on ubuntu-24.04 or ubuntu-latest
    (which is currently 24.04), so the upgrade is safe across the
    deployment surface.

    Functionally identical: --update=none means "do not overwrite an
    existing file" - same as --no-clobber, but without the
    portability warning. The local cache dir at ~/.apt-deb-cache can
    accumulate the same name from a previous run, and so can
    /var/cache/apt/archives; both call sites want skip-if-exists.

    Two call sites in install.sh:
      - seed:     sudo cp --no-clobber -> sudo cp --update=none
      - snapshot:      cp --no-clobber ->      cp --update=none

