commit 7df2714169df3598da2a5ad4828d4decd15033d8
Author: assisted-by-ai (Bot Account) <228987186+assisted-by-ai@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Sat May 16 04:25:58 2026 -0400

    ci: isolate bot-authored events into a separate concurrency group

    Manually testing @claude review on this PR surfaced a race: the
    Claude action posts its review as claude[bot], that comment fires
    this same workflow again, and with the existing single-group
    `cancel-in-progress: true` concurrency setting the bot-triggered
    re-run cancelled the in-flight human-triggered review *mid-flight*
    - after the prompt had been assembled but before the Claude API
    call posted anything visible to the PR. Live run on PR #92:

      - 07:58:42 issue_comment run #25956755466 starts
        (actor=assisted-by-ai, body contains @claude)
      - 07:58:55 final prompt assembled, about to call Claude API
      - 07:58:56 issue_comment run #25956759124 starts
        (actor=claude[bot], body lacks @claude)
      - run #25956759124 enters the same concurrency group, cancels
        #25956755466
      - #25956759124 itself then gets job-level skipped by the
        \'@claude\' substring filter, but the damage is done
      - #25956755466 ends \'cancelled\'; PR gets no review

    The job-level `if:` was the only existing filter for bot
    comments; concurrency runs BEFORE that filter, so by the time
    the bot run is rejected on substring grounds it has already
    cancelled the in-flight work.

    Fix: per-actor-class concurrency grouping. GitHub\'s standard
    \'[bot]\' suffix on App accounts (claude[bot],
    github-advanced-security[bot], dependabot[bot], chatgpt-codex-
    connector[bot], ...) is the natural split:

      group: ${{ github.workflow }}-${{ ... }}-${{ endsWith(github.actor, \'[bot]\') && \'bot\' || \'human\' }}

    Bot-triggered runs (which always skip via the \'if:\') land in
    a separate group from human-triggered reviews, so they only
    cancel each other. The in-flight human review runs to
    completion.

    Edit on the source-of-truth at consumer-templates/ + the
    byte-identical in-dmf mirror at .github/workflows/ (dmf is its
    own consumer per agents/github-actions.md G-A-005). Other
    consumer repos pick up the fix at the next
    pkg_update_consumer_workflows propagation pass.

    codex-review.yml does NOT need the same fix: its triggers are
    pull_request + workflow_dispatch only (no issue_comment), so
    codex\'s own review comments do not re-trigger its workflow.

