    the composite action to @master, so a PR\'s install.sh isn\'t
    the version that runs in self-CI).

    On second look, the codex finding doesn\'t pass the bar:

    1. agents/github-actions.md G-A-004 explicitly endorses @master
       for first-party cross-repo `uses:` references:
       "First-party reusable workflows (org-ai-assisted/... /
        Kicksecure/... / Whonix/...) reference each other by branch
        name (@master) on purpose - single-source-of-truth update
        propagation."

    2. The two existing composite actions in this repo
       (install-deps, shellcheck) follow exactly the same pattern -
       their action.yml header docs `@master` for cross-repo
       usage, and they\'re only invoked from local-* workflows via
       `./` (local ref) within the same repo. Neither has a
       dogfood-on-PR mechanism. The new composite action matches that
       precedent.

    3. install.sh is ~25 lines, passes shellcheck, and the
       pre-push static gate enforces R-001/R-010/R-020 etc. before
       merge. Code review covers the rest. Adding a dedicated
       self-test workflow to catch an install.sh regression that
       shellcheck+review wouldn\'t catch is over-engineering.

    4. The codebase\'s explicit policy (docs/scorecard-known-false-
       positives.md) treats PinnedDependenciesID alerts on @master
       refs as accepted false positives - the trust model puts
       github.com in scope as a trust root for CI (security.md
       "Threat model A"), so SHA-pin ceremony for internal refs is
       not the goal.

    So removing the self-test workflow. The PR returns to its prior
    shape: composite action @master in the three reusable workflows,
    no special dogfood mechanism.

commit c11898eb3c692cd991a14052a5fbe89af75fd4fc
Author: assisted-by-ai (Bot Account) <228987186+assisted-by-ai@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Sat May 16 04:04:36 2026 -0400

    ci: add self-test workflow that dogfoods PR\'s composite action

    Codex review on PR #92 flagged a dogfood gap (P1): the reusable-*
    workflows pin the new composite action to @master, so a dmf PR
    that modifies .github/actions/apt-install-with-cache/install.sh
    gets self-CI against the @master copy of install.sh, NOT the
    PR\'s copy. A breaking change could merge undetected.

    The structural fix (use ${{ env.DMF_REF }} in the @ref portion)
    is rejected by GitHub Actions: step-level `uses:` does NOT accept
    context expressions in the @ref. Per the Variables docs: "you
    can use the env context in any key in a workflow step except
    for the id and uses keys". The github context is similarly
    restricted in practice (community discussion #63675).

    This commit adds a dedicated self-CI workflow that uses a *local*
    action reference (`uses: ./.github/actions/apt-install-with-cache`)
    which IS bound to the PR\'s checkout. The workflow:
      - triggers only when .github/actions/apt-install-with-cache/
        changes (path filter)
      - installs `hello` via the PR\'s composite action
      - verifies hello got installed
      - verifies install.sh\'s snapshot phase populated
        ~/.apt-deb-cache/hello_*.deb
      - regression-guards apt\'s normal permission posture
        (/var/cache/apt/archives root:root 0755 parent,
        _apt:root 0700 partial/ - the whole point of the
        runner-owned sidecar design)

    So a PR that introduces a breaking install.sh change fails this
    workflow before merging, closing the dogfood gap.

commit 7dcc93b6e627ba14fe643b3db607e5675d437f88
Author: assisted-by-ai (Bot Account) <228987186+assisted-by-ai@users.noreply.github.com>
