    ci: extract apt-install-with-cache helper to satisfy R-100

    The inline run: blocks for the apt-cache seed/snapshot logic were
    ~15 lines each with control flow (if-guards, array initialization,
    nullglob shopt). Per bash-style-guide.md R-100, substantial bash
    logic with control flow does not belong inside workflow YAML run:
    blocks: shellcheck only sees real .sh files, not YAML blocks, so
    inline shell silently bypasses linting.

    This commit:

    - Extracts the seed/install/snapshot logic into ci/apt-install-with-cache.sh,
      a single-purpose helper with the full strict-mode quintet (R-010),
      the 'AI-Assisted' header (R-002), and a CI guard mirroring
      ci/coverity-check-secrets.sh.
    - Each reusable workflow's install step becomes a single-line
      invocation of the helper (or 3 lines for coverity, which still
      expands APT_PACKAGES env into an array for safe shell-metacharacter
      handling; under the R-100 ~5-line threshold and no control flow).
    - Cache keys now include the helper script's hashFiles() so a
      change to the seed/snapshot logic invalidates the cache.
    - Comments shrunk to one-line pointers to the script header
      (R-150: state rationale once per file).
    - The "earlier revisions" journaling comment in reusable-bandit.yml
      is removed (rot-prone, per the "no task-history comments" rule).
    - bandit's developer-meta-files checkout moved before the install
      step because the install step now calls a dmf script.

    AGENTS.md adherence:
      R-001 ASCII only:                    pass
      R-002 'AI-Assisted' header:          pass
      R-010 strict-mode quintet (6 lines): pass
      R-020 ${var} braces:                 pass
      R-025 array init under nounset:      pass (seed_debs, new_debs)
      R-060 long flag names:               pass (--no-clobber, --parents,
                                           --non-interactive, --yes,
                                           --no-install-recommends, etc.)
      R-061 no combined short flags:       pass
      R-062 -- end-of-options:             pass (apt-get, cp, mkdir)
      R-100 substantial bash out of YAML:  pass
      R-102 no bash/sh prepend:            pass
      R-120 no rm (using cp):              pass
      R-150 rationale once per file:       pass (lives in script header)
      R-151 no rot-prone comments:         pass
      shellcheck --external-sources:       pass
      G-A-007 cache poisoning:             pass (cached .debs re-verified
                                           by apt-get install on next run)

commit fb2ac4f84b26b25e623edab4b616341414aa02b7
Author: assisted-by-ai (Bot Account) <228987186+assisted-by-ai@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Fri May 15 18:54:02 2026 -0400

    ci: cache .debs in runner-owned dir, never touch apt's permissions

    Refactor #2 of the apt-cache pattern in three reusable workflows
    (reusable-cppcheck, reusable-bandit, reusable-coverity).

    Background: /var/cache/apt/archives is root:root 0755 with an
    _apt:root 0700 'partial/' subdirectory. apt drops privileges during
    the download phase, and partial/ holds unverified bytes; 0700 is
    deliberate. actions/cache runs tar as the unprivileged runner user,
    which can't read partial/.

    Earlier attempts to make actions/cache's tar work with the system
    path:

      A) sudo chown -R "$(id -u):$(id -g)" /var/cache/apt/archives
         Clobbers apt's permission model. apt-get install also
         recreates partial/ 0700 every run, so the chown has to be
         re-applied after install - a perpetual fight.

      B) sudo chmod o+w /var/cache/apt/archives + path: *.deb
         Drops world-writable on a system directory. Better than (A)
         for partial/ specifically, but worse on the parent - any
         local process can now plant .debs there.

    Both touch system permissions. Neither is necessary. New approach:

      - Cache ~/.apt-deb-cache (a runner-owned directory). actions/cache
        tars it as the runner without any permission gymnastics; the
        system /var/cache/apt/archives is never the cached path.
      - Install step uses a seed/snapshot pattern:
          seed:     sudo cp ~/.apt-deb-cache/*.deb /var/cache/apt/archives/
                    so apt-get install finds and reuses the cached .debs
                    instead of re-downloading.
          install:  sudo apt-get install ... (unchanged)
          snapshot: cp /var/cache/apt/archives/*.deb ~/.apt-deb-cache/
                    to capture any newly-downloaded .debs for the next
                    run. No sudo - apt's .debs are root:root mode 0644
                    (world-readable).
      - shopt -s nullglob + (( ${#arr[@]} > 0 )) guards make the empty-
        glob case (first run, or no new downloads) a no-op without
        relying on '|| true'.

    apt's /var/cache/apt/archives stays exactly as Ubuntu ships it -
    root:root 0755 parent, _apt:root 0700 partial/ - across runs.

    Mirrors what awalsh128/cache-apt-pkgs-action does (cache a
    runner-owned dir, shuttle .debs in/out); we just don't take the
    Marketplace dependency.

    Observed on
    https://github.com/org-ai-assisted/kloak/actions/runs/25935205795

commit dc2d0a7eb93782f04f5a7d8e5d097827c226c5b0
Author: assisted-by-ai (Bot Account) <228987186+assisted-by-ai@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Fri May 15 18:33:37 2026 -0400

    ci: switch apt cache to *.deb glob + chmod o+w (preserve apt ownership)

    Refactor of the prior chown-based approach. Three reusable workflows
    (reusable-cppcheck, reusable-bandit, reusable-coverity) had a
    "Prepare apt cache directory" step that ran:

      sudo chown -R "$(id -u):$(id -g)" /var/cache/apt/archives

    and cached `path: /var/cache/apt/archives`. This worked but had two
    problems:

    1. apt-get install (run via sudo) recreates the archives/partial/
       subdirectory as _apt:root mode 0700 regardless of the parent's
       ownership. The cache-save post-step then tars the cached path
       as the unprivileged runner user, fails to read partial/, and
       emits 'Failed to save: tar exit code 2'. The cache never
       persists across runs.
    2. Even with a post-install re-chown to address (1), recursively
       chowning /var/cache/apt/archives to the runner clobbers apt's
       normal permission model. The _apt:root mode 0700 on partial/
       exists for a real reason: apt drops privileges during the
       download phase, and unverified packages in partial/ should not
       be readable by other local users.

    New approach:

    - chmod o+w /var/cache/apt/archives (not chown -R) - the parent
      needs to be writable by the runner so actions/cache can extract
      .deb files on restore, but ownership stays root:root and
      partial/ keeps its _apt:root 0700.
    - path: /var/cache/apt/archives/*.deb - glob to .deb files only.
      Excludes partial/ (unreadable by runner) and lock (irrelevant).
      The cache-save post-step never traverses partial/, so apt
      recreating it as _apt:root mode 0700 after each install is
      harmless.

    Observed on
    https://github.com/org-ai-assisted/kloak/actions/runs/25935205795

commit 733632d498e454b173767b76fdf42835af68a894
Author: assisted-by-ai (Bot Account) <228987186+assisted-by-ai@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Fri May 15 18:10:21 2026 -0400

    ci: re-chown apt cache after install to fix cache-save tar warning

    The reusable-cppcheck, reusable-bandit and reusable-coverity workflows
    all chown /var/cache/apt/archives before the install step so that
    actions/cache can restore into it without sudo. apt-get install then
    recreates the archives/partial/ subdirectory as _apt:root mode 0700,
    which the unprivileged runner user cannot read. When actions/cache's
    post-step runs at job cleanup it tars the cached path as that user
    and bails out with:

      /usr/bin/tar: ../../../../../var/cache/apt/archives/partial:
      Cannot open: Permission denied
      ##[warning]Failed to save: "/usr/bin/tar" failed with error:
      The process '/usr/bin/tar' failed with exit code 2

    The job still succeeds (just a warning), but the cache never
    persists across runs, so each invocation re-downloads packages
    from apt.

    Fix: re-take ownership of /var/cache/apt/archives at the end of
    the install step. The save step then reads partial/ cleanly and
    the cache actually gets written.

    Observed on
    https://github.com/org-ai-assisted/kloak/actions/runs/25935205795

