commit aa11f961652e979c728b24c1d7e6c0854782184b
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Fri May 15 19:21:25 2026 +0000

    ci(security): route dogfood checkout ref through env (DMF_REF)

    Follow-on to the fork-PR guard. Routes the dogfood-vs-master
    checkout-ref expression through a job-level env var (DMF_REF) in
    all six reusables that share the pattern, matching the org-wide
    env-routing convention already used for JOB_STATUS / BASE_REF /
    CPPCHECK_PATHS / etc.

    Before:

        with:
          repository: org-ai-assisted/developer-meta-files
          ref: ${{ github.repository == 'org-ai-assisted/...' && github.sha || 'master' }}

    After:

        env:
          DMF_REF: ${{ github.repository == 'org-ai-assisted/...' && github.sha || 'master' }}
        ...
        with:
          repository: org-ai-assisted/developer-meta-files
          ref: ${{ env.DMF_REF }}

    Files (single source of truth, propagated to consumers only via
    reusable @master tracking - no consumer-side ref changes):

    - reusable-bandit.yml
    - reusable-codeql.yml
    - reusable-cppcheck.yml
    - reusable-pre-push-static.yml
    - reusable-scorecard.yml
    - reusable-secrets-audit.yml

    The job-level fork-PR guard added in the previous commit remains
    the actual mitigation for actions/untrusted-checkout/medium alert
    #15 - CodeQL's dataflow tracker follows env-var references, so
    indirection alone doesn't break the source-to-sink path. Env
    routing is added here for convention consistency and to keep the
    attacker-influenceable expression out of the with:/ref: site, not
    because it independently closes the alert.

    YAML still parses; agents/pre-push-static.sh passes; no expression-
    injection sites regressed (find-expr-injection scan: 0 hits).

commit cfe9646be2b0e4d1e9cf497d4905655a9b4258ac
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Fri May 15 19:11:24 2026 +0000

    ci(security): add fork-PR guard to pre-push-static + secrets-audit

    Closes CodeQL actions/untrusted-checkout/medium alert #15
    ("Checkout of untrusted code in trusted context") and the same
    latent pattern in reusable-secrets-audit.yml.

    Both reusables share a dogfood checkout that resolves to
    ${{ github.sha }} when the caller IS developer-meta-files, falling
    back to 'master' otherwise. On a pull_request event from a fork
    that path would run an attacker-controlled script in the runner.
    Trigger is pull_request (not pull_request_target) and permissions
    are contents: read only, so the blast radius is bounded - but the
    guard is the standard org-wide mitigation and the four other
    reusables that share this pattern (bandit, codeql, scorecard,
    cppcheck) already carry it.

    Adding:

        if: github.event.pull_request.head.repo.full_name == github.repository
            || github.event_name != 'pull_request'

    at job level. Net effect:

    - Fork PRs: job skipped (closes the alert path).
    - Same-repo branch PRs: job runs (dogfooding preserved; org members
      all have write, trusted by agents/security.md threat model A).
    - push / workflow_dispatch: job runs (event_name discriminator).
    - Cross-repo callers (derivative-maker, helper-scripts, ...): job
      runs and the dogfood ref already resolves to 'master', so no
      behavior change there.

    YAML still parses; agents/pre-push-static.sh passes.

