commit 16c3c5d270b5c9fd0536cbe76bfc7d97a7df2073
Author: assisted-by-ai (Bot Account) <228987186+assisted-by-ai@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Fri May 15 08:22:08 2026 -0400

    agents/github-actions.md: correct G-A-006 singleton ownership

    The doc said singleton reusables own the singleton lock and
    consumers either omit or mirror it. Same caller-name resolution
    rule that bites cancellable reusables applies here too: a
    reusable declaring `group: ${{ github.workflow }}` expands to the
    caller's workflow name, which the caller already holds. With
    cancel-in-progress: false the reusable would block-wait on its
    own caller's lock and deadlock the run (different surface error
    from the cancellable case but same root cause).

    The actual implementation has always put the singleton on the
    consumer wrapper (consumer-coverity.yml) and omitted concurrency
    on the reusable (reusable-coverity.yml even carries an explicit
    inline comment to that effect). Update the doc to match the code.

    This is purely a doc-vs-code consistency fix - no code changes,
    but paired with the reusable-claude/codex fixes in this branch
    it completes the "caller owns concurrency, reusable omits" rule
    for every G-A-006 pattern (cancellable AND singleton).

