commit d3611fa993061584cfe16efa25ce841ff4d4e84f
Author: assisted-by-ai (Bot Account) <228987186+assisted-by-ai@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Fri May 15 06:38:01 2026 -0400

    ci(actions): add end-of-options '--' to sudo wrapper everywhere

    Append '--' to the sudo_prefix array at every definition site:
      - install-deps/action.yml (apt step + install-self step)
      - install-deps/install-genmkfile.sh
      - install-deps/install-helper-scripts.sh
      - shellcheck/action.yml

    After expansion the sudo invocation becomes
    'sudo --non-interactive -- <command>', explicitly terminating
    sudo's option parsing before the command name. Today the command
    arg is always a literal (apt-get, genmkfile, ./usr/bin/genmkfile)
    so sudo's implicit "stop options at first non-dash arg" rule
    makes this a no-op. The '--' is defense in depth against a future
    edit that prepends an attacker-influenced value before the
    command and accidentally creates a flag-smuggling vector.

    Same idea applied one layer down: the shellcheck composite action
    also gains '--' before 'shellcheck' in its apt-get install call,
    matching the install-deps pattern.

commit 0e51677903ccef43c138549cc49278456ed3d1cb
Author: assisted-by-ai (Bot Account) <228987186+assisted-by-ai@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Fri May 15 06:35:00 2026 -0400

    agents/github-actions.md: correct G-A-006 reusable-side examples

    The doc previously cited reusable-claude-code-review.yml and
    reusable-codex-review.yml as live examples of "differentiate the
    group key with a per-call input the caller doesn't replicate".
    Both reusables' keys carry the SAME PR/issue-number
    disambiguator as their callers, so under github.workflow = the
    caller's name (in both contexts) the locks collide. That is the
    deadlock G-A-006 warns about, not an example of the
    differentiation pattern.

    This commit:

    - Moves both AI-review reusables from the "differentiate" list
      to the "omit" list (where they now belong after the companion
      reusable-side edits in this branch).
    - Tightens the differentiate-pattern description to spell out
      WHY codeql's `${{ inputs.language }}` works (the caller's
      basic `${{ github.workflow }}-${{ github.ref }}` does not
      carry that token).
    - Updates the Issue-comment paragraph to point at the consumer
      templates (not the reusables) as the source of truth for the
      PR/issue-number disambiguator. Cross-references back to the
      Reusable-side concurrency rule for the rationale.

commit d4ea9c336b177999c00fc76bec51c42aa9722d90
Author: assisted-by-ai (Bot Account) <228987186+assisted-by-ai@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Fri May 15 06:34:59 2026 -0400

    reusable-codex-review: drop concurrency block (self-cancel bug)

    Same root cause as the claude reusable: github.workflow inside
    a reusable expands to the caller's name, so the reusable's
    concurrency group collides with the caller's. The codex reusable
    is currently in DISABLED state (`if: false` kill-switch on the
    active job), but the concurrency block on a re-enable would re-
    introduce the deadlock. Drop it now so the archived block stays
    identical-shaped when re-enabled.

    Fix per agents/github-actions.md G-A-006: reusables omit
    concurrency entirely when the caller's cancellable group covers
    the call. consumer-codex-review.yml already carries the
    cancellable group.

    Reusable-side comment replaced; added an explicit "do NOT re-add
    a concurrency block" note for the re-enable procedure.

commit 671f38b8859704e6c8321d92054daeea028b74b2
Author: assisted-by-ai (Bot Account) <228987186+assisted-by-ai@users.noreply.github.com>
Date:   Fri May 15 06:34:58 2026 -0400

    reusable-claude-code-review: drop concurrency block (self-cancel bug)

    The reusable's concurrency group resolves identically to the
    caller's because github.workflow inside a reusable expands to
    the caller's workflow name. With cancel-in-progress: true the
    reusable cancels its own caller the moment it tries to acquire
    the slot - Actions logs "Canceling since a deadlock was detected
    for concurrency group: ..." and the workflow fails before any
    job registers. consumer-claude-code.yml has logged 40 consecutive
    failures over three days (100% failure rate since the workflow
    was created), all with total_count: 0 jobs and 1-2 second
    duration; the merged consumer-side R3 pre-filter from PR #82 is
    innocent.

    Fix per agents/github-actions.md G-A-006: reusables omit
    concurrency entirely when the caller's cancellable group covers
    the call (the consumer wrapper already carries the PR-
    disambiguated group required for issue_comment events).

    Reusable-side comment replaced to document why the block is
    absent and to point at the G-A-006 rule.

