    Template-substituted ${{ inputs.apt-packages }} into a shell run:
    block expanded the caller-supplied value as literal text before
    bash parsed the script. ';', '|', and '$()' would all reinterpret
    as shell syntax instead of arriving as data. Move the input
    through env: (matching the shellcheck composite action's pattern)
    so expansion happens at runtime where the special characters are
    inert. Unquoted $APT_PACKAGES preserves the space-separated
    package-list word-splitting the original behavior depended on.

    No exploit today - every current caller passes a literal YAML
    string. Removes the footgun for the next caller who plumbs a
    PR-controlled value through.

