    agents: third-round spec fixes per review

    Six precision fixes addressing the third-round review on PR #60:

    - Config-load example split into required-key and optional-key
      loops. Required keys (project-name, canonical-repos) hard-fail
      on missing/empty; optional keys (apt-packages, build-command)
      use yq's `// ""` default and pass an empty value through to
      the reusable. Brings the example in line with the
      required/optional annotations in the parameter table.
    - yq install comment corrected: Ubuntu 24.04 (which ubuntu-latest
      currently resolves to) ships kislyuk's python-yq jq-wrapper,
      not mikefarah's Go yq. The `// ""` and `-r` syntax is for
      python-yq.
    - Coverity gate-placement section gains an implementation-detail
      paragraph: today's reusable sets COVERITY_TOKEN /
      COVERITY_EMAIL in jobs.<id>.env: at job level (lines 196-199).
      The rewrite must move those onto the individual gated steps
      that need them; otherwise the spec's "secrets path is never
      reached on a non-canonical run" claim is not actually true.
    - "Scheduling in universal templates" renamed to "Scheduling in
      byte-identical templates" and expanded: the policy covers both
      universal and parameterized templates. consumer-coverity.yml
      added as a third example - its uniform org-wide cron slot is
      safe because Coverity's per-project daily quota bounds each
      project independently of the cron concentration.
    - "Hub is a consumer of itself" bullet rewritten to qualify that
      the hub opts into only the templates that make sense for it
      (universal set, no C/C++), rather than implying every template
      is installed in the hub's .github/workflows/.
    - Parameter-ownership intro gains a byte-identical-wrapper-
      contract clarifier: categories describe what consumer-template
      wrappers do, not whether the reusable's input surface is
      technically overridable. Direct callers from a hand-written
      local-*.yml can still pass any workflow_call.input.

commit 83c18d1f1ecea6e83262408b1e2d6dd2cc476df0
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Tue May 12 13:12:46 2026 +0000

    agents: tighten consumer-template spec per second-round review

    Seven precision fixes addressing the second-round review on PR #60:

    - Coverity dry-run reclassified from "kept as reusable input" to
      "hardcoded in reusable at false". The previous wording promised
      a wrapper-level override that the byte-identical example did
      not actually provide. Production runs never submit in dry-run;
      manual dry-runs happen in a development branch.
    - Required vs optional annotations added to every dm-consumer.yml
      key in the parameter-ownership table. The hard-fail validation
      rule is updated: missing required key is a hard error; missing
      optional key falls through to the reusable's built-in default
      behavior.
    - "Completes neutral" replaced with "completes success with all
      expensive steps skipped". Actions has no first-class neutral
      status for a shell-driven gate; the previous wording overstated
      what the mechanism delivers.
    - cppcheck.prepare-command wording corrected: source-tree prep,
      not apt-installed deps. apt installs in prepare-command would
      be uncached. If a real apt-deps need appears, the right answer
      is a dedicated cppcheck.apt-packages key with its own cache.
    - The "workflow_call.inputs goes away" claim is narrowed to
      apply only to dm-consumer.yml-owned values. Hardcoded-in-wrapper
      values (codeql's language, build-mode) stay as workflow_call
      inputs and are passed by byte-identical with: blocks;
      hardcoded-in-reusable values stay with reusable defaults.
    - Wrapper-shape example caption fixed: removed "including
      developer-meta-files itself" which contradicted the
      directory-layout section saying the hub does not install
      consumer-coverity.yml.
    - yq -r added to the example invocation. Note added that Debian
      ships Mike Farah's Go yq (different from python-yq); the
      implementation must verify the exact flag set.

