commit c457acfc05b7f7b19ae06d64627efa00daab70c2
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Tue May 12 07:56:16 2026 +0000

    codeql-actions.yml: add 'actions' language CodeQL scan for dev-meta-files

    Enables CodeQL's GitHub Actions workflow security analysis (GA April
    2025, https://github.blog/changelog/2025-04-22-...): script-injection
    in run blocks, missing-workflow-permissions, dangerous-unverified
    inputs, unversioned-immutable-action, etc. dev-meta-files itself
    ships the reusable workflows the org consumes, so this is the
    highest-value target - a finding here propagates to every downstream
    caller.

    New file: .github/workflows/codeql-actions.yml
    - Self-consumer wrapper around reusable-codeql.yml with
      language: actions
    - Same @master 'normal consumer' form as the other dmf wrappers
    - Triggers: push to master, pull_request, workflow_dispatch.
      No cron (see below).
    - Standard top-level concurrency block (cancel in-progress on
      superseding push)
    - security-events: write at the job level for SARIF upload

    Why a new file rather than baking actions-scan into reusable-codeql:
    the reusable's contract is one (language, build-mode) pair per call,
    and the concurrency key already uses inputs.language as a
    disambiguator. Folding a second language in would muddy that,
    waste scan minutes on every c-cpp / python call, and still
    wouldn't cover the repos that have no codeql.yml at all. A
    small standalone consumer wrapper is easier to propagate
    byte-identically.

    Why cronless: the same file is intended to land in every consumer
    repo via pkg_update_consumer_workflows (see helper-script change in
    this commit). Per-repo cron slots would force a post-cp rewrite -
    push/PR/dispatch triggers cover scan-on-change adequately, and
    rule-refresh re-scans can be triggered manually from the Actions
    tab when needed.

    Helper-script change:
    - pkg_update_consumer_workflows workflow_list: drop codeql.yml,
      add codeql-actions.yml. codeql.yml was never actually safe to
      propagate (kloak: language=c-cpp + manual build; helper-scripts:
      language=python; each has a unique cron slot - copying one over
      the other would silently break the destination repo's scan).
      codeql-actions.yml is genuinely byte-identical across repos so
      it belongs in the list; codeql.yml stays per-repo.

