    touched usr/bin/dm-packaging-helper-script (the file-level R-010
    and R-120 checks only scan files in the change set).

    R-010 strict-mode quintet: script header was missing the sixth
    strict-mode line. Added 'shopt -s shift_verbose' to the existing
    block alongside inherit_errexit. No behavior change beyond a
    diagnostic log line when 'shift' runs past argv end.

    R-120 'rm not safe-rm': false-positive hits on two real git
    subcommands -

      usr/bin/dm-packaging-helper-script:1169
        git remote rm origin || true
      usr/bin/dm-packaging-helper-script:1368
        git rm -- "debian/compat" || true

    Neither is a filesystem 'rm' invocation; both touch git's index
    or remote config. Extended the existing carve-out alongside the
    'safe-rm' and 'shred' exclusions to match
    'git[[:space:]]+(remote[[:space:]]+)?rm[[:space:]]'. Inline
    comment block documents the rationale for each carve-out (parallel
    treatment with shred's explicit-overwrite semantics).

    Gate now passes on this branch with the pkg_update_if_exists
    helper added in the previous commit.

commit 6210a4a4e86c6591d405e472f641ca559534d658
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Mon May 11 22:13:25 2026 +0000

    dm-packaging-helper-script: add pkg_update_if_exists helper

    Reusable Utility function for the common pattern of "drop an
    updated copy of a template/config file into packages that already
    ship it, leave the rest alone." Stages the file, skips the commit
    on no-op runs via the existing nothing_to_commit guard, and uses
    "update <basename>" as the default commit message (overrideable
    via optional third arg).

    Usage:
      pkg_update_if_exists <source_path> <destination_path> [<commit_msg>]

      source_path       - full path to the canonical version (typically
                          under "${derivative_maker_source_code_dir}/...")
      destination_path  - full path inside the current package
      commit_msg        - optional; defaults to
                          "update <basename-of-destination>"

    Style matches extract_description_from_debian_control: required-
    parameter validation in the multi-elif printf '%s\n' "${red}${bold}
    FATAL ERROR..." pattern, locals declared at the top of the
    function, 'true "INFO: ..."' diagnostic messages (R-130), '--'
    end-of-options on cp / git invocations (R-062).

commit b29bf79f779030f7d0652146d5dbbb989b490baa
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Mon May 11 22:03:53 2026 +0000

    reusables: drop wrapper-colliding concurrency in bandit/cppcheck/scorecard

    The previous commit on this branch removed concurrency from the
    scorecard self-consumer wrapper. That's the wrong direction: this
    repo's established precedent is to omit 'concurrency:' inside the
    reusable (see reusable-pre-push-static.yml and reusable-secrets-audit.yml,
    both of which carry an explicit "would deadlock" comment), because
    'github.workflow' inside a called reusable resolves to the caller's
    workflow name and produces an identical group key to the wrapper's.

    This commit aligns three reusables with that precedent:

    - reusable-scorecard.yml: drop concurrency block (was the deadlock
      source), add the precedent-style explanation comment, revert the
      docstring "do NOT add wrapper-level concurrency" paragraph that
      the previous commit introduced.
    - reusable-bandit.yml: same fix - same '${{ github.workflow }}-${{ github.ref }}'
      group key would deadlock against cross-repo bandit.yml wrappers.
    - reusable-cppcheck.yml: same fix - same collision pattern.
    - scorecard.yml self-consumer wrapper: restore the concurrency
      block the previous commit removed; the wrapper is the
      unambiguous owner of the group key.
    - agents/github-actions.md: clarify G-A-006 with a new
      "Reusable-side concurrency" paragraph documenting the two safe
      patterns (omit; or differentiate group key with a per-call
      input).

    Net effect against origin/master: 3 reusables drop their
    concurrency block; documentation now explains why. Cross-repo
    consumer wrappers in other repos that already carry a top-level
    concurrency block (kloak, helper-scripts, etc.) stop deadlocking
    without any change on their side.

    Reusables left alone because their group key already differentiates
    (no deadlock risk): reusable-codeql.yml (inputs.language),
    reusable-claude-code-review.yml + reusable-codex-review.yml
    (PR/issue-number disambiguator), reusable-coverity.yml
    (intentional singleton).

commit 8183b3c4d201e9159f8c0c8ba9e3f968b3159ae3
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Mon May 11 21:50:53 2026 +0000

    scorecard: drop wrapper-level concurrency to fix deadlock with reusable

    Both reusable-scorecard.yml and the self-consumer wrapper declared
    the same cancellable group ('${{ github.workflow }}-${{ github.ref }}').
    Inside a called reusable github.workflow and github.ref resolve to
    the caller's values, so the two locks have identical names. Actions
    detects this as a deadlock and cancels the run with:

      Canceling since a deadlock was detected for concurrency group:
      'Scorecard-refs/heads/master' between a top level workflow and
      'scorecard'

    reusable-codeql.yml sidesteps this by including inputs.language in
    its group; scorecard has no analogous per-call differentiator, so
    the wrapper omits its block and lets the reusable own the policy.

    Cross-repo consumer wrappers (kloak, helper-scripts, derivative-maker,
    tb-updater, whonix-firewall, genmkfile) still carry the duplicate
    concurrency block and remain affected; those will be updated
    separately per the docstring warning added here.

