commit 2533a53f58f4bf2633f06dc693a2ef1bae0a8fb4
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Mon May 11 15:18:56 2026 +0000

    step-summary-emit: bash-style-guide cleanups (R-030, R-050, R-060, R-102)

    Manual style-guide pass uncovered five rule violations the static
    gate's Tier-1 regex set does not catch:

      R-060 (long flag names): sed -n -> sed --quiet
      R-030 (printf format fixed, data in data string): the unknown-
            flag error printf had the value embedded in the format
            string via '%s'; switch to printf '%s\n' "..." style.
            Refactor: hoist into a die_usage() helper so every arg-
            parsing error path uses one consistent form, cleaning up
            the multi-statement-on-one-line case arms (R-071 spirit).
      R-050 (blank line after function close): trap_cleanup() in
            test_step_summary_emit.sh ran into the trap registration
            line below it without a separator.
      R-102 (don't prepend interpreter when shebang suffices): seven
            'bash -- "${HELPER}"' invocations in the new code; the
            helper is chmod +x with #!/bin/bash, so the prepend is
            redundant. Direct invocation matches project precedent.
            Pre-existing 'bash --' on test_path iteration in
            test-github-org-tools.sh:71 left alone (out of scope and
            defends against forgotten chmod on per-test files).

    Markdown-emission printf calls (the panel writer) keep their
    multi-character format strings ('## %s\n\n', '| %s | %s |\n',
    etc.) because R-030's intent (no dynamic content in the format,
    no injection vector) is satisfied - the format is fixed; only
    data flows through %s. The "always 'printf %s\\n'" template
    doesn't accommodate markdown structure cleanly, and splitting
    each markdown line into a separate printf forces R-042
    violations (blank-line separators around tables/headings).
    Worth a future agents/bash-style-guide.md clarification.

    Gate + full mock-API suite still green (28/28 pass).

