commit 43c1d9fdf814d4b61a192bcad239b638d2348ffa
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Mon May 11 12:30:01 2026 +0000

    agents+ci: add reusable-pre-push-static.yml + dmf consumer + imperative CLAUDE.md

    Adds a CI mirror of agents/pre-push-static.sh as a reusable
    workflow plus a dogfooding consumer wrapper, so PRs to dmf (and
    to any repo that adopts the reusable) get blocked at merge if
    they violate R-001 ASCII, bash -n, shellcheck, or any Tier-1
    style-guide rule -- regardless of whether the developer
    installed the local pre-push hook.

    reusable-pre-push-static.yml:
      - Two checkouts: caller repo (fetch-depth=0 for git diff
        history) and dmf at master (or caller's commit when dmf is
        self-consuming, per the secrets-audit precedent).
      - Installs shellcheck via apt so the gate's strongest check
        runs in CI even when not present in the dev env.
      - Base ref resolved via a single GitHub expression (input >
        PR base > origin/master), keeping the run: block thin per
        R-100.
      - No concurrency block: github.workflow inside a reusable
        resolves to the original caller, so a group declared here
        would deadlock with the caller's group.

    pre-push-static.yml: dogfood consumer wrapper. Triggers on
    pull_request and push-to-master. Standard cancellable
    concurrency.

    CLAUDE.md: was a passive 'See AGENTS.md' redirect. Replaced
    with a numbered imperative that names the gate command and the
    hook-install one-liner directly. AI sessions that read
    CLAUDE.md now get the action item without a second hop.

    AGENTS.md: hoisted the gate from a row in the table to a
    top-level bold imperative paragraph above the table. The table
    row stays for indexing.

    Note for future AI sessions: this commit was prompted by the
    realization that this session ignored the original
    'See AGENTS.md' redirect and introduced R-001 violations
    (em dashes in commit titles) that the gate would have caught.
    The directive form aims to make that failure mode harder.

    https://claude.ai/code/session_018rti4CCm2SQ3PWKa7jRt7p

commit 63017e570da68a9f170d0e556e0bddc56efb6e59
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Mon May 11 12:11:10 2026 +0000

    agents/pre-push-static: fix base-ref expansion bug + add Tier-1 R-rule checks

    Bug: base_ref="${1:-@{u}}" mis-parses. Bash terminates the outer
    ${...} at the first '}', returning '@{u' (or $1) and appending
    a literal '}' to the result. No-arg case reconstructs '@{u}' by
    accident; any explicit base-ref arg gets a spurious '}' glued
    on, breaking git rev-parse with rc=2. Replaced with a plain
    conditional.

    New checks (Tier 1 of bash-style-guide scriptability tier):
      R-010 strict-mode quintet present in head -100 (raised from
            the implicit limit so long-docstring scripts pass).
      R-011 no 'set +o errexit' toggling.
      R-042 no blank-line printf/log separators.
      R-051 no inline trap command (must be named function).
      R-070 ';;' on own line.
      R-081 no shellcheck source=/dev/null suppression.
      R-090 'has' not 'command -v' (allowlist for the documented
            R-093 bootstrap exceptions, including this script).
      R-102 no bash/sh prepend on script invocations (runs on shell
            + yml files; .md skipped because the style guide doc
            self-cites the bad pattern).
      R-120 'safe-rm' not 'rm' (conservative; comments + shred
            excluded).
      R-130 bare ':' as no-op on own line (deliberately narrow:
            does NOT flag the ': "${var:=default}"' parameter-default
            idiom used in github-org-lib.bsh).

    Self-exemption for the gate itself: R-042, R-051, R-081, R-102
    checks skip agents/pre-push-static.sh because its grep needles
    appear literally in its own doc comments and/or code lines (same
    class of meta-exception as R-093 for command -v).

    https://claude.ai/code/session_018rti4CCm2SQ3PWKa7jRt7p

commit 3c747533e596dfb055281b09a3d7c3b893da005a
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Mon May 11 12:11:10 2026 +0000

    agents/bash-style-guide: add R-102 (don't prepend bash/sh; trust shebang)

    Surfaced by kloak's codeql.yml which used:
      build-command: bash build.sh

    R-102: when a script has a #!/bin/bash shebang and executable
    bit, invoke as path/script.sh -- not "bash script.sh" (redundant)
    and certainly not "sh script.sh" (overrides shebang, breaks
    bash-specific syntax silently). Exception: bootstrap before the
    executable bit is set, or surfaces that don't honor shebangs.

    Also updates R-100's example (which violated the new R-102).

    https://claude.ai/code/session_018rti4CCm2SQ3PWKa7jRt7p

commit 824dcda7eaf20dd1be6286908c505cddd2cb7205
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Mon May 11 12:11:10 2026 +0000

    agents/github-actions: correct G-A-001 -- no contexts in jobs.<id>.uses:

    Empirical evidence from a propagation attempt across 8 consumer
    repos: GitHub workflow file validator rejects vars.X in
    jobs.<id>.uses: with "Unrecognized named-value: 'vars'", same
    failure mode as github.* in that position. The official docs say
    "You cannot use contexts or expressions in this keyword".
    Community posts claiming vars is allowed appear to conflate
    uses: with with:/secrets: blocks where vars IS allowed.

    There is no parameterization workaround. Each first-party org's
    consumer workflows must hardcode the canonical/mirror owner.
    Cross-org consumption (Whonix-org calling Kicksecure/dmf...) is
    expressed by hardcoding "Kicksecure/" in those wrappers.

    https://claude.ai/code/session_018rti4CCm2SQ3PWKa7jRt7p

