commit 4bacff762543b9affec44af6199c69059ee8e22d
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Sun May 10 14:20:17 2026 +0000

    dm-github-org-security-report: dump filtered code-scanning alerts

    New tool that pulls /orgs/{org}/code-scanning/alerts?state=open
    and emits a markdown table on stdout. Status messages go through
    log to stderr so the report itself is cleanly redirectable:

       dm-github-org-security-report --report > /tmp/sec.md

    Two modes (one is required):

       --report  filter to code-fixable tools (CodeQL, Bandit,
                 cppcheck, Coverity). Drops Scorecard alerts which
                 are project-policy shaped (MaintainedID,
                 DependencyUpdateToolID, etc - documented as known
                 false positives in
                 docs/scorecard-known-false-positives.md and rarely
                 "edit a line of code to fix").

       --all     every open alert across the org.

    The CODE_TOOLS_RE regex constant is the single source of truth
    for which tools count as "code-fixable"; adding a new SAST tool
    to the project means adding it there.

    Output is a 7-column table: repo, tool, severity, rule, path,
    line, message. Pipe characters in alert message text are
    backslash-escaped so they do not break column boundaries.

    Live verified against org-ai-assisted (Free plan, 100 open
    alerts):
       --report -> 1 row (the only CodeQL finding -
                    msgcollector py/file-not-closed at
                    usr/libexec/msgcollector/alert:55)
       --all    -> 100 rows (1 CodeQL + 99 Scorecard)

    Mock test: GET_orgs_org-ai-assisted_code-scanning_alerts fixture
    with 1 CodeQL + 2 Scorecard alerts (one with no file association,
    one with a real path) verifies:
       --report keeps the CodeQL row and drops both Scorecard rows
       --all    keeps all three rows
       missing-mode-flag invocation dies with exit 64

    Full suite 25/25 (was 24).

    Token scope: needs 'security_events' (classic) or 'Code scanning
    alerts: read' (fine-grained). The 'repo' scope our existing PAT
    carries already covers public-repo alerts.

commit a9bb5d26bdc588b6c7ab6e1e528a26c302da1f18
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Sun May 10 13:53:00 2026 +0000

    POLICY_MEMBERS: org-wide kill of repo deploy keys + TODO.md

    Two changes from continued web-settings sweep (Batch O1):

    POLICY_MEMBERS body now includes
    "deploy_keys_enabled_for_repositories: false". The org-level
    toggle (PATCH /orgs/{org}) is plan-independent (Free works) and
    PATCH-settable; live-tested 2026-05 returned HTTP 200 and the
    GET reads back as false. With this on, no repo in the org can
    attach a deploy key even by an admin. Earlier per-repo /keys
    audit returned [] on every repo we sampled - this is why,
    locked in as policy.

    Label updated to "members policy (default-perm=read, no member
    create, no deploy keys)" so the operator-facing log line names
    the new field. Mock test assertions in test_dm_apply.sh and
    test_dm_dryrun.sh updated to match. Full suite 24/24.

    Rationale comment added to the data file: deploy keys are a
    write-capable bypass of user-level perms with legitimate uses
    (CI push) but the cost on a mirror-of-mirrors org outweighs the
    benefit. Repos that genuinely need a deploy key would use a
    fine-grained PAT or a GitHub App instead.

    TODO.md added as the operator-facing follow-up list:
      - Org profile fields (display name, description, blog) -
        suggested values for org-ai-assisted.
      - Org-level web_commit_signoff_required - the
        cleaner one-call PATCH alternative to the per-repo path
        documented in agents/github-policy-canonical-vs-mirror.md.
      - PERSON adrelanos personal-profile field revamp (blog
        Impressum -> canonical, bio empty, social_accounts empty).
      - dm-github-personal-policy filter for adrelanos before
        running --apply against him (Pages clobber risk on
        PasswordTrainer / travis.debian.net standalone projects).
      - Recap of future tightenings already in agents docs.

    Nothing in TODO.md is automated by this PR - it's a manual
    checklist for operator follow-up.

commit d9388e83fd905902647549e0124c5f730995d1cf
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Sun May 10 13:35:38 2026 +0000

    dm-github-personal-policy: hide primary email from public profile

    New account-wide step in dm-github-personal-policy: PATCH
    /user/email/visibility {"visibility":"private"} once per --apply
    invocation. Goal: enforce "primary email never advertised on the
    public profile" as steady-state policy across PERSON and BOT
    accounts.

    Auth: PATCH /user/email/visibility implicitly acts on the
    token-authed user. Calling it with a token belonging to user A
    while running against user B would mutate A's email visibility,
    not B's. Guard added: a /user lookup at script start, then the
    PATCH only fires when authed login matches target_user. On
    mismatch, a clear notice line names both logins and explains the
    skip. The /user GET runs in dry-run too (it's a read), so the
    authed-user gate behaves identically across modes.

    Token scope: classic PAT needs user:email; fine-grained needs
    "Email addresses: write". Without it the PATCH returns HTTP 404
    ("Not Found", per GitHub's misleading scope-missing message),
    which fires a regular policy_api_call warn - operators see
    exactly which scope is missing in the warn body.

    Data file:
      POLICY_USER_EMAIL_PRIVATE entry. No __OWNER__/__REPO__
      placeholders since /user is implicitly the authed user;
      the call site uses policy_api_call directly (not via
      policy_apply_repo dispatcher).

    Tests:
      test_dm_personal_apply / test_dm_personal_dryrun assert the
      SKIP line (GET_user fixture login=assisted-by-ai vs target
      personal-test-user). PATCH_user_email_visibility fixture
      added (returns 204) for any future test that runs against
      a target matching the authed login.

    Live verified: --apply against assisted-by-ai (matching login)
    emitted the expected WARN at PATCH time because this PR's PAT
    lacks user:email scope. Public profile already shows email=null
    (operator flipped via UI manually), so steady state is as
    desired; the script will keep it that way once an appropriately
    scoped token is used.

    Auth section in --help updated to call out the user:email scope
    and the same-login requirement.

