commit ea80da60a1917f9a3eef0c4ca4ce06472e2ab00d
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Sun May 10 09:41:44 2026 +0000

    agents/github-actions.md: document sha_pinning_required intentionally off

    GitHub's org / repo Actions setting sha_pinning_required, when true,
    rejects any uses: ref that is not a 40-char commit SHA (no floating
    tags like @v4 or @master). Useful in threat models that distrust
    github.com ref-resolution; we do not currently model that.

    Add a short subsection under "Action SHA pinning" explaining why
    the toggle stays off:

      - First-party reusable workflows reference each other by
        @master on purpose for single-source-of-truth update
        propagation (G-A-004 above).
      - Threat-model-A in agents/security.md explicitly trusts
        github.com and the org's own repos as transport. SHA-pin
        ceremony on internal refs is over-engineering for threats
        the CI surface does not model.
      - Third-party action refs are already SHA-pinned individually
        per the existing discipline; the org toggle adds nothing.

    Found while surveying the repo's GitHub web settings (Actions ->
    General -> "Require approval for all outside collaborators" plus
    "Require commit SHA pinning" sibling toggle); flagging the
    deliberate "off" state in docs so a future audit does not flip it
    without understanding the rationale.

