commit b147a561c554567af302f710e3dec52d2233ccbd
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Fri May 8 16:04:02 2026 +0000

    add ls-remote-aware push gate, share between dm-push and packaging helper

    New shared library so dm-push and dm-packaging-helper-script can
    both decide "does this branch need to be pushed" via the same code:

      usr/libexec/developer-meta-files/git-helpers.bsh
        internal_git_diff_local
          Compares refs/heads/<branch> vs refs/remotes/<remote>/<branch>.
          No network round-trip; only as fresh as the last fetch. A
          concurrent pusher who advanced the remote since our last fetch
          will not be seen by this gate; the eventual push is rejected
          non-fast-forward and the caller must re-fetch and retry.
        internal_git_diff_remote
          Queries the remote via 'git ls-remote'. One metadata-only
          network round-trip per call. Sees concurrent pushes.
        internal_git_diff
          Dispatcher. Default is _local; set DM_GATE_LS_REMOTE=1 to opt
          in to _remote.

    Both compare commit SHAs rather than tree contents: amend, rebased
    message, or cherry-pick of an already-applied change all produce a
    new commit SHA with an unchanged tree, and all need to be pushed.
    Tree-level 'git diff' would falsely report "no diff" in those cases.

    dm-push:
      - Source git-helpers.bsh (with in-tree fallback for dev runs).
      - queue_branch_refspec calls the dispatcher; default behavior is
        _local, change with DM_GATE_LS_REMOTE=1.
      - Push uses 'git push --atomic --porcelain' so multi-ref pushes to
        the same remote either all-succeed or all-fail, and per-ref
        status is machine-readable for diagnostics.

    dm-packaging-helper-script:
      - Source git-helpers.bsh; remove the inline duplicate gate.
      - pkg_git_push_remotes takes a mode argument: 'local' (default,
        no network) or 'remote' (ls-remote, authoritative). The single
        existing caller (pkg_git_changelog_bump_inner_inner) calls
        'pkg_git_push_remotes local'.
      - Push uses --atomic --porcelain (same rationale as dm-push).

    Style:
      - ASCII only (R-001).
      - AI-Assisted marker on the new library (R-002).
      - Errors via 'die', warnings via 'log warn' from log_run_die.sh
        (R-040, R-110); both callers source log_run_die.sh before
        git-helpers.bsh.
      - Locals declared at top of function with assignments separated
        (R-021).
      - Library has no top-level set / shopt; entry-point scripts
        already set the strict-mode quintet.

commit fb7cd10788ce23b0fa80f786c06b52bc77b0d9e0
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Fri May 8 15:50:21 2026 +0000

    claude-code-review: document allowed_users drop + OIDC requirement

    Two gotchas worth documenting in the reusable's docblock so a
    future maintainer doesn't re-introduce the same mistakes:

    1. The upstream action no longer accepts 'allowed_users' (it
       silently warns 'Unexpected input(s)' and drops the value). We
       gate at the workflow 'if:' instead, which runs before the
       runner spins up.

    2. The action uses OIDC federation to mint an elevated
       GITHUB_TOKEN; 'id-token: write' is mandatory on the calling
       job's permissions block.

commit e1934877169ededeba6810863dc1e0e3c5c7e2f8
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Fri May 8 15:49:18 2026 +0000

    claude-code-review: restore id-token, drop unrecognized allowed_users

    Reverts a misdiagnosis. Verified against a live workflow log:

      ##[warning]Unexpected input(s) 'allowed_users', valid inputs are
        [..., 'allowed_bots', 'allowed_non_write_users', ...]

      Requesting OIDC token...
      OIDC token successfully obtained
      Exchanging OIDC token for app token...
      Using GITHUB_TOKEN from OIDC

    Two corrections to the reusable:

    1. Restore 'id-token: write' on the job-level permissions block.
       The action federates the runner's id-token to an Anthropic-
       controlled GitHub App which mints a higher-privilege GITHUB_TOKEN
       used to post review comments. Without the permission the next
       run would fail with 'Could not fetch an OIDC token'.

    2. Stop passing 'allowed_users:' to the action - it has been removed
       upstream (the action emits 'Unexpected input(s)' and silently
       drops the value). The valid replacements are 'allowed_non_write_users'
       and 'allowed_bots'; for our roster (org members with write access)
       neither applies. The job-level 'if:' gate added in the previous
       reusable commit already enforces the roster check at the workflow
       layer, so the action-internal gate is no longer needed.

    Also restore id-token: write in the dev-meta-files self-consumer.

