commit 2d12db0f340d610d201da65b688cc36b5663194d
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Fri May 8 15:20:59 2026 +0000

    claude-code-review: drop id-token, gate on @claude + allowed-users

    Two changes to the reusable workflow:

    1. Drop 'id-token: write' from the job-level permissions block.
       The action authenticates to api.anthropic.com via a static
       ANTHROPIC_API_KEY; OIDC federation is unused. Removing the
       permission honors least-privilege (an OIDC token, if forged or
       leaked, can authenticate to cloud-provider integrations).

    2. Add a job-level 'if:' gate. On comment-triggered events
       ('issue_comment' / 'pull_request_review_comment') the runner
       used to spin up on EVERY comment - the action would then no-op
       internally if the body lacked '@claude', burning runner minutes
       for nothing. The new gate also enforces the allowed-users
       roster at the workflow level (defense in depth - the same check
       already runs inside the action). Net effect: random external
       commenters cannot drain the org's ANTHROPIC_API_KEY budget by
       spam-mentioning @claude, and unauthorized actors cannot spin
       up a runner at all.

commit fcdf63bc343f84ccc579aa5c13bcd2f1de0bdeb9
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Fri May 8 13:47:06 2026 +0000

    reusable-cppcheck: drop 'style' from default enable; fix exit-code comment

    Two fixes after the first real PR run (kloak#5) exercised the
    reusable end-to-end and revealed a wrong mental model in the
    exit-code comment.

    (1) cppcheck's --error-exitcode=N triggers on ANY finding at
        ANY enabled severity, NOT only the 'error' severity (despite
        what the flag's name suggests). Comment in the reusable
        claimed otherwise; corrected.

    (2) Consequence of (1): with the previous default
        'warning,style,performance,portability' enable list, every
        'style' finding (variableScope, constVariablePointer,
        constParameterCallback, ...) triggers CI failure. kloak#5
        surfaced ~10 such findings on src/kloak.c, all pre-existing
        and none bug-class.

        New default: 'warning,performance,portability'. 'style' is
        available as an opt-in via the 'enable' input when a repo
        has been pre-audited and wants the broader scan. Repos
        starting from a non-style-clean baseline can adopt the
        reusable without first having to clean up every style nit.

    The kloak#5 findings remain printed (they're at the 'style'
    severity which the default no longer enables, so they aren't
    even scanned anymore - the next pass with style enabled will
    re-surface them). Action on those is a separate cleanup PR
    deciding whether each style finding is a real refactor target
    or a false positive worth a #cppcheck-suppress comment.

commit 7055e1b750fe568e07718bb60be676ab705af7d1
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Fri May 8 13:44:48 2026 +0000

    reusable-cppcheck: drop unsupported '--' separator

    cppcheck does NOT accept '--' as end-of-options separator -
    it rejects with 'unrecognized command line option: "--"' and
    exits 1 before scanning anything. Verified locally against
    cppcheck 2.13.0 (Ubuntu 24.04 archive).

    Per R-062, '--' should only be added to tool invocations
    where the actual binary supports it. This was missed during
    the reusable's introduction; caught by the first real PR run
    (kloak#5).

    Removing '--' is safe here because the only positional we pass
    is 'inputs.paths' which is a workflow input under our control;
    no risk of an attacker-controlled string starting with '-'.

    Added a note in the comment block so the next person tempted
    to re-add it has a pointer to why.

commit f069717bcd9cfd0eb5738be964ea4ed6d15cb511
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Fri May 8 13:34:03 2026 +0000

    github-actions: rename reusables to 'reusable-<name>.yml'

    File-naming convention codified in agents/github-actions.md as
    G-A-005: reusable workflows in this repo carry a 'reusable-'
    prefix; consumer-wrapper filenames don't. Trade-off survey
    landed on this over '_<name>.yml' or 'reusable_<name>.yml'
    because (a) it sorts together visually, (b) GitHub renders the
    file list with explicit prefix grouping, (c) it removes the
    need for '-self' / 'codex.yml' suffix workarounds in this repo
    which holds both kinds.

    Rename:
      codeql.yml              -> reusable-codeql.yml
      scorecard.yml           -> reusable-scorecard.yml
      claude-code-review.yml  -> reusable-claude-code-review.yml
      codex-review.yml        -> reusable-codex-review.yml
      coverity.yml            -> reusable-coverity.yml
      cppcheck.yml            -> reusable-cppcheck.yml
      bandit.yml              -> reusable-bandit.yml

    Self-consumer wrappers in this repo simplify accordingly:
      scorecard-self.yml      -> scorecard.yml         (no longer
                                                        conflicts)
      codex.yml               -> codex-review.yml      (no longer
                                                        conflicts)
      claude-code.yml         -> unchanged              (was already
                                                        consumer-style)

    Self-consumer 'uses:' lines updated to point at './.github/
    workflows/reusable-<name>.yml' (path remains relative for
    dogfooding - see G-A-004 / earlier comments).

    Cross-repo consumers in helper-scripts, kloak, security-misc,
    derivative-maker get a parallel 'developer-meta-files/.github/
    workflows/X.yml@master' -> 'reusable-X.yml@master' update on
    their respective master branches in the same change cycle.
    The PR-execution window where 'X.yml@master' no longer resolves
    is bounded by the cross-repo push gap (~minutes) and is
    consciously accepted.

    docs/scorecard-known-false-positives.md path references
    refreshed to the new reusable filenames.

commit 4f457091efe44f493cb187149d5288e18ef7171f
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Fri May 8 13:05:50 2026 +0000

    docs: catalogue Scorecard known false positives + agents pointer

    New file docs/scorecard-known-false-positives.md collects the
    signals Scorecard reports that are intentional architectural
    choices in this org rather than findings to act on:

      DependencyUpdateToolID  consumer repos with no dependabot.yml
                              because action SHAs live in this repo.
      PinnedDependenciesID    '@master' reusable refs per G-A-004.
      MaintainedID            freshly created repos (auto-resolves
                              after 90 days).
      SASTID transient        partial score for ~30 days after
                              CodeQL adoption while the commit-
                              history-with-coverage window rolls
                              forward.
      Dockerfile FROM stage   multi-stage local stage references
                              flagged as unpinned.

    Plus a section listing what we DO act on so reviewers know which
    Scorecard signals are real (SecurityPolicyID, BranchProtectionID,
    CodeReviewID, FuzzingID, real pip/Dockerfile pins).

    agents/github-actions.md gains a brief 'See also' pointer at the
    new doc so AI agents working on workflow changes find it
    naturally.

    The 'don't drop CodeQL path filters' guidance is captured in the
    SASTID-transient section as an explicit cost-vs-coverage trade-
    off, per the 'CI cost is an issue' direction.

commit c7ce7385b1f55ba6f1e838ac68362005995a4f34
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Fri May 8 12:58:31 2026 +0000

    github-actions: dogfood reusables on this repo

    Add self-consumer wrappers that call the locally-hosted reusable
    workflows so PRs to this repo run them too:

      scorecard-self.yml -> ./.github/workflows/scorecard.yml
      claude-code.yml    -> ./.github/workflows/claude-code-review.yml
      codex.yml          -> ./.github/workflows/codex-review.yml

    Local-path './...' references rather than cross-repo '@master':
    a PR modifying a reusable then exercises its own changes during
    the PR's CI run, instead of running the master version of the
    reusable that the PR is changing. Self-test by construction.

    Filename suffixes ('-self', shortened 'codex.yml') exist because
    GitHub Actions cannot have two workflow files with the same name
    in one repo; the reusables already occupy 'scorecard.yml' and
    'codex-review.yml'.

    Skipped (no relevant source code in this repo):
      codeql.yml      - no Python / no C / no JS; CodeQL has no
                        bash extractor
      coverity.yml    - same languages-supported gap
      cppcheck.yml    - no C / no C++
      bandit.yml      - no Python

commit d4a5506ff8ada488666025236f9b99f7fc35137c
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Fri May 8 12:38:21 2026 +0000

    github-actions: add reusable cppcheck + bandit workflows

    Free open-source local-runnable static analyzers for the C and
    Python halves of the org's source. Complement Coverity Scan -
    different rule sets, no third-party-service dependency, can
    run on a developer machine via plain 'cppcheck' / 'bandit'.

    cppcheck.yml (reusable):
      inputs: paths, enable, extra-args, prepare-command,
              timeout-minutes
      apt-installs cppcheck, runs '--enable=warning,style,
      performance,portability --inline-suppr --error-exitcode=2
      --quiet'. Exits non-zero only on cppcheck 'error' severity;
      warnings/style print but do not fail CI (per the typical
      cppcheck-in-CI shape).

    bandit.yml (reusable):
      inputs: paths, severity-level, confidence-level, skips,
              prepare-command, timeout-minutes
      apt-installs bandit, runs '-r' with the requested severity
      / confidence floors. Per-line '# nosec' comments are the
      preferred suppression vs the global skips input.

    Both reusables expose the same prepare-command pattern as the
    codeql reusable so consumers with genmkfile-tagged source files
    ('*.c#tag', '*.py#tag') can re-use ci/codeql-prepare.sh-style
    symlinks before the linter runs.

    Bandit is preferred over a Python static-checker for security
    patterns specifically (hardcoded passwords, shell=True
    subprocess, weak crypto, eval). It complements pyflakes /
    pylint which focus on correctness / style.

