    notification address.

commit 967c40935ac91d3fde236e12619bf6505cd1682d
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Fri May 8 11:46:03 2026 +0000

    github-actions: add reusable Coverity Scan workflow

    Replaces vapier/coverity-scan-action and the per-repo inline
    curl+tar+cov-build flow with one centralized reusable. Three
    consumers (helper-scripts, kloak, security-misc) call this with
    their repo-specific build deps and project name.

    The orchestration scripts (check-secrets, download with md5+sha256
    verify, python default cov-build, submit) live under ci/ in this
    repo and are checked out into the runner alongside the consumer's
    repo. Refactored from helper-scripts/ci/coverity-*.sh; the only
    change is dropping the implicit 'cd $(dirname ...)/..' so each
    script trusts its cwd, which the reusable workflow controls.

    Reusable inputs:
      apt-packages     space-separated build deps to apt-install
      build-command    bash invoked under cwd=consumer-repo-root, with
                       ./cov-analysis/bin/cov-build available; empty
                       defaults to the Python cov-build flow
      project-name     scan.coverity.com project; falls back to
                       vars.COVERITY_PROJECT, then to the repo basename
      timeout-minutes  job timeout (default 30)
      canonical-repos  comma-separated owner/repo allow-list for the
                       push/schedule events; forks must use
                       workflow_dispatch since they lack the secrets

    Secrets read from caller's namespace via 'secrets: inherit':
      COVERITY_SCAN_TOKEN, COVERITY_SCAN_EMAIL.

    No third-party Action footprint - the only external trust roots
    are scan.coverity.com (the cov-analysis tarball, gated by the
    project token + md5 verified, optionally sha256 hard-pinned via
    .coverity-tool-sha256.expected in the consumer repo) and
    actions/checkout / actions/upload-artifact (already in use across
    the org).

commit 2b24f6075c22a2ea1b6974cb45d93d69117b3c07
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Fri May 8 11:35:06 2026 +0000

    ai-reviews: secrets:inherit + unify codex bot list

    Two changes - both align with the "secrets are org-wide, not per-
    repo" policy.

    1. Drop the workflow_call.secrets schema from both reusables. The
       action steps now read 'secrets.ANTHROPIC_API_KEY' /
       'secrets.OPENAI_API_KEY' directly from the caller's namespace.
       Consumer wrappers pair this with 'secrets: inherit' instead of
       the 5-line explicit secret-mapping block. Less per-repo
       boilerplate; aligns with org-level secret storage where the
       secret name is fixed across consumers anyway.

    2. Set codex-review.yml inputs.allow-bot-users default to the same
       "adrelanos,ArrayBolt3,assisted-by-ai" canonical list used by
       claude-code-review.yml inputs.allowed-users. Single roster
       string everywhere. The codex-action treats this list as a
       "bot-bypass for actor-write-access" gate; including humans is a
       no-op for them (humans are gated separately by GitHub-side
       write access) and keeps the list shape uniform across both AI
       review reusables.

commit abb886d1f279b864d213e1275e5fb8a4a7af8425
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Fri May 8 11:27:26 2026 +0000

    ai-reviews: hardcode org-canonical reviewer rosters in reusables

    Unify the allow-lists that were previously duplicated by every
    consumer wrapper. Move them into the reusable workflows as input
    defaults:

      claude-code-review.yml:
        inputs.allowed-users default = "adrelanos,ArrayBolt3,assisted-by-ai"
      codex-review.yml:
        inputs.allow-bot-users default = "assisted-by-ai"

    Single source of truth: update the roster here, every consumer
    wrapper picks it up on the next workflow run. No org-level Actions
    variables needed (would have been a cleaner mechanism but requires
    admin:org / fine-grained 'actions_variables' permission, which the
    test PAT lacks).

    Inputs remain optional - a per-repo override (e.g. an external
    OSS contributor that needs @claude trigger access on one repo
    only) can still pass an explicit value via 'with: allowed-users:'.

commit 965554b7887d0d293ecb5246e968ea9688a87735
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Fri May 8 11:20:47 2026 +0000

    github-actions: add reusable Claude/Codex AI review workflows

    Centralizes the AI-review boilerplate that was previously duplicated
    in kloak's .github/workflows/{claude-code,codex-review}.yml. Two
    'workflow_call' reusables, parameterized via inputs:

      claude-code-review.yml:
        inputs:  allowed-users, timeout-minutes
        secrets: anthropic-api-key
        triggers (caller decides):  pull_request +
                                    issue_comment + review-comment

      codex-review.yml:
        inputs:  allow-bot-users, pr-ref, sandbox, prompt,
                 timeout-minutes
        secrets: openai-api-key
        triggers (caller decides):  pull_request + workflow_dispatch

    Both reusables retain the safety properties of the original kloak
    inline workflows:

      * Workflow-level 'permissions: contents: read' default; jobs
        upgrade only what they need.
      * Concurrency keys account for issue_comment / pr-ref so reviews
        on different PRs don't cancel each other.
      * codex-review fork-PR skip is preserved (paid OPENAI_API_KEY
        must not run on attacker-controlled fork code on the
        pull_request trigger; workflow_dispatch is the manual override
        path for fork-PR review).
      * SHA-pinned action versions with verifiable tag comments.

    Schedule cannot live in workflow_call (G-A-002), so caller wrappers
    own their own triggers. The kloak wrappers shrink from ~57/95 lines
    inline to ~30 lines each (header + triggers + 1 'uses:' job each).

