commit bc7e9f16ed6992dadb15d7d866994f3533412d6a
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Mon May 4 16:03:36 2026 +0000

    ci/tests: capture rc via '|| rc=$?' instead of toggling errexit

    Cleaner than 'set +o errexit; cmd; rc=$?; set -o errexit' for the
    exit-code capture. With errexit on, a bare 'out=$(failing-cmd)'
    aborts the script; the '|| rc=$?' suffix tells errexit "this
    failure is handled" while still letting the previous-line
    short-circuit-with-pipefail behavior of the surrounding script
    stay intact. rc=0 default before the assignment keeps nounset
    happy if the command succeeds.

    No behavior change. Same three test files touched as before
    (test_dm_dryrun.sh, test_dm_personal_dryrun.sh,
    test_dm_personal_refuses_org.sh).

commit c0207cd19674acd85b5ede0f36150ccfad2d5ba4
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Mon May 4 15:22:34 2026 +0000

    dm-github-{,personal-}policy: replace counter+summary with one warn flag

    Per-status counters (ok / warn / dry / skip) and the end-of-run
    summary block in dm-github-policy added noise without signal: the
    operator already sees each event's log line at the moment it
    happens, and a CI / cron caller only needs to know "did anything
    go wrong, yes or no" via the exit code. Drop both.

    What replaces the api_record / counter tempfile / grep --count
    machinery:

    - POLICY_WARN_FILE env var. Caller (dm-github-policy main,
      dm-github-personal-policy top-level) creates a tempfile, exports
      the path, and registers an EXIT trap to clean it up. The lib's
      policy_api_call and _policy_upsert_ruleset call _policy_mark_warn
      on every warn path, which appends a single byte to the file.
      Single-byte appends are atomic across concurrent backgrounded
      writers (PIPE_BUF >= 4096 on Linux), so the per-repo & loop
      needs no extra mutex.
    - After the main loop, the tool tests '[ -s "${POLICY_WARN_FILE}" ]'
      and exits 1 if the file is non-empty, 0 otherwise.

    Tests:

    - Drop the brittle '\]: ok: |\[WARN\]:' regex check in
      test_dm_dryrun.sh and test_dm_personal_dryrun.sh. Replace with
      an exit-code check (rc != 0 -> warn slipped through). The lib
      short-circuits dry-run before any ghorg_api call, so no warn
      path can fire structurally; the rc check is a defensive belt
      rather than a load-bearing assertion.
    - Drop the '=== summary ===' substring assertion from
      test_dm_dryrun.sh: there is no summary block to assert on
      anymore.

commit 4b69d2ce7e08f92175b086797e440692716b0003
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Mon May 4 14:57:36 2026 +0000

    ci/test_clone_dryrun: redirect stderr too

    The printf -> log conversion (14bf373) sends every user-facing line
    to stderr (log_run_die.sh's stecho). test_clone_dryrun captured
    out="\$(github-org-clone --dry-run ...)" without 2>&1 and so
    collected only stdout, which is now empty. The two DRY-RUN: clone
    lines and the '2 repos to process' header are all in stderr; every
    substring grep against \${out} consequently failed.

    Earlier local 10/10 passes were a false positive: my reinstall
    only refreshed the two dm-github-* tools, leaving the old
    printf-based github-org-clone on PATH. Reinstalling the lot
    reproduces the CI failure locally and confirms the fix.

commit 94ec851bdb3168a46b5351f93def4b5c3780448d
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Mon May 4 14:51:03 2026 +0000

    ci/tests: tighten dry-run ok:/warn anti-pattern

    The previous attempt (edf9ed4) used ' ok: ' as the discriminator
    for "a real API call's success line slipped through dry-run." That
    matched the summary-count line dm-github-policy --dry-run prints
    at the end:

       <script> [NOTICE]:   ok:      0

    which contains the substring ' ok: ' (single space, ok, colon,
    space) inside the wider '  ok:      0'. test_dm_dryrun consequently
    reported a false positive on every dry-run.

    Tighten the anti-pattern to '\]: ok: ' - the level-tag-to-content
    junction the API-call-success line has but the indented summary
    line does not. policy_api_call's 'log notice "ok: <label>
    [<status>]"' produces '<script> [NOTICE]: ok: ...' (one space
    between ']:' and 'ok:'); the summary 'log notice "  ok:
    ${n}"' produces '<script> [NOTICE]:   ok: ...' (three spaces),
    which the new pattern does not match.

    Verified by running the full ci/test-github-org-tools.sh locally
    under CI=true: 10/10 pass.

commit edf9ed4debdb8288c090309c740adb1025c48f3e
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Mon May 4 14:47:23 2026 +0000

    ci: update dryrun tests for log-prefixed output

    The recent printf -> log conversion (14bf373) shifts all user-
    facing output to log_run_die.sh's format:

       <script> [NOTICE]: <content>

    so tests that anchored on column 0 of the structured prefix now
    fail to match. Three updates:

    - test_clone_dryrun.sh: '^2 repos to process' -> fixed-string
      '2 repos to process under' (no anchor needed; substring inside
      the log notice line).

    - test_dm_dryrun.sh + test_dm_personal_dryrun.sh: the negative
      '^ok:|^warn:' check switches to ' ok: |\[WARN\]:'. The earlier
      pattern would silently pass after the conversion (no line ever
      starts with literal 'ok:' or 'warn:' anymore, so the dry-run-no-
      real-call invariant was no longer being enforced). The new
      pattern looks for the substring ' ok: ' that policy_api_call's
      success branch produces and the '[WARN]:' level tag that its
      non-2xx branch produces - either inside the log line means a
      real PUT/PATCH/DELETE ran.

commit 14bf373674a83a7eedc7fc44a21d5241bc1d23a3
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Mon May 4 14:43:38 2026 +0000

    github-{org,policy}-* + lib: convert all stdout/stderr to log

    The bash style guide previously carved out a 'structured prefix
    output stays as printf' exception for lines like 'DRY-RUN: ...',
    'ok: ...', 'warn: ...', '=== summary ==='. Drop that exception:
    every line written to the user goes through log notice / log warn
    / log error so the operator gets the script-name + level tag in
    front of the message. Tests grep for substrings inside the line,
    so the structured words ('DRY-RUN:', 'ok:', etc.) stay grep-able
    even though they no longer anchor at column 0.

    Files converted:
      - usr/libexec/developer-meta-files/github-policy-lib.bsh
        (policy_api_call + _policy_upsert_ruleset)
      - usr/bin/dm-github-policy            (apply + audit + summary)
      - usr/bin/dm-github-personal-policy   (audit_one)
      - usr/bin/github-org-clone            (clone_or_update_one + main)
      - usr/bin/github-org-fork             (fork + collision + configure
                                             + main)
      - usr/bin/github-org-push             (push_one + main)
      - usr/bin/dm-github-fork-sync         (drop a leftover blank
                                             'log notice ""')

    ghorg_require_deps now hardcodes the full base set
    (curl jq sanitize-string git) instead of taking the extra deps
    positionally. The policy tools never exec git themselves but the
    whole family is meant to run in a git-using operator environment;
    demanding git unconditionally is simpler than threading per-tool
    extras and saved the per-callsite SC2119 disables.

    Style guide updated: 'Output to user goes through log' replaces
    the prior printf-vs-log distinction. Reserves printf for file
    writes, subshells feeding other tools, and printf -v. Notes that
    blank-line separators are noise once every line carries a
    [NOTICE]: prefix.

