commit 60c263ce2e9ff0dae350e462d79d349a28c1d7df
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Mon May 4 00:14:03 2026 +0000

    usr/bin/dm-github-personal-policy: per-repo lockdown for personal accounts

    Mirrors the per-repo subset of dm-github-policy (which targets orgs)
    for individual user accounts. Designed to harden a personal account
    against malicious fork PRs that would otherwise burn Actions minutes
    on workflows triggered by external contributors.

    Settings applied per repo:
      - Fork-PR contributor approval = all_external_contributors
      - Default workflow GITHUB_TOKEN permissions = read
      - Allowed Actions = selected (github-owned + verified creators)

    Repos in scope: public, non-archived, non-fork repos owned by the
    user given on the CLI. Iterated via ghorg_list_repos which already
    paginates per_page=100 with GHORG_MAX_PAGES=100 cap (10000 repo
    ceiling, far above any personal-account need).

    Modes:
      - <username>            : apply
      - <username> --dry-run  : print planned PUT/PATCH calls
      - <username> --audit    : read-only inspection of current state

    Repo-level body schema for /repos/{owner}/{repo}/actions/permissions
    differs from the org endpoint (uses 'enabled' bool instead of
    'enabled_repositories' string); rest of the bodies match
    dm-github-policy directly.

    Idempotent and apply-only (PATCH/PUT are upsert; never disables a
    setting that was already on). Best-effort error handling: a failure
    on one repo logs a warn and the loop continues, so 1 archived repo
    returning 403 doesn't kill the whole run for ~335 other repos.

    Test target: assisted-by-ai. Production target: adrelanos.

    https://claude.ai/code/session_01U5dqsVj1msLQMiCemkuddP

commit d82afbaa6dbcf64af2197dc98f4a37530f3d0730
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Sun May 3 23:14:44 2026 +0000

    github-org-fork: combine_alt skips empty patterns

    Codex P2 review of 1add4eb: passing --exclude "" (e.g. from a wrapper
    forwarding an optional regex via --exclude "${EXCLUDE_RE:-}") would
    have produced exclude_re="()". ghorg_filter_names then runs
    'grep -v -E "()"', and the empty alternative matches every line, so
    every repo gets dropped. The script silently no-ops with
    "no source repos matched."

    Pre-this-PR behaviour was that an empty --exclude left exclude_re=''
    and ghorg_filter_names treated it as no filter. The accumulator
    introduced the regression.

    Fix: combine_alt skips empty list entries. If every entry is empty,
    the result is the empty string - matching the pre-PR no-filter
    semantics. Preserves the original codepath for wrappers that
    optionally pass --exclude "".

    Verified locally with synthetic combine_alt invocations:
      no entries           -> ""
      ("foo")              -> "(foo)"
      ("foo" "bar")        -> "(foo)|(bar)"
      ("" "foo")           -> "(foo)"
      ("foo" "")           -> "(foo)"
      ("")                 -> ""
      ("" "")              -> ""

    https://claude.ai/code/session_01U5dqsVj1msLQMiCemkuddP

commit 1add4eb2f20e804fc8d9b54034bb87f5d9c88bb8
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Sun May 3 22:53:52 2026 +0000

    github-org-fork: drop unsupported '--' from git check-ref-format

    Codex P1 review of 04322e4: 'git check-ref-format --branch -- <X>'
    returns usage error 129 on git 2.43+ because the --branch form does
    not accept '--' as an end-of-options separator. The previous fix
    ALWAYS failed validation, so --sync-branches silently rejected every
    repo and never actually synced.

    Verified locally on git 2.43.0: '--' is not supported by any form
    of check-ref-format (basic, --branch, --normalize). Drop '--' and
    validate as a full refname:

      git check-ref-format "refs/heads/${default_branch}"

    The 'refs/heads/' prefix ensures the resulting argv element never
    starts with '-', so the missing '--' end-of-options does not create
    a shell-level arg-injection path from a hostile API response.

    Manually tested against:
      main           - OK
      master         - OK
      release/2026   - OK   (hierarchical, what codex flagged in round 1)
      v2.0+stable    - OK   ('+' was rejected by the homegrown allowlist
                             that codex flagged in round 2)
      -dash          - OK   (git allows leading '-' in ref components;
                             arg-injection blocked by 'refs/heads/' prefix)
      a..b           - FAIL (git rejects '..' per its rules)
      ''             - FAIL (trailing '/' rejected)

    https://claude.ai/code/session_01U5dqsVj1msLQMiCemkuddP

commit 04322e4085ee4b67600934c5402a32660104dffd
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Sun May 3 22:50:08 2026 +0000

    github-org-fork: git check-ref-format for branch validation; accumulate --include/--exclude

    Codex review of 03aeaa4 raised two issues:

    1. P2: branch-name allowlist '^[A-Za-z0-9._/-]+$' was still too strict.
       Git allows additional valid characters (e.g. '+'), so any repo whose
       default branch contains them was silently skipped with a warn.

       Fix: replace the homegrown allowlist with 'git check-ref-format
       --branch -- "${default_branch}"', which enforces git's actual
       ref-name rules (no leading '-', no '..', no doubled '/', no
       control chars, no '.lock' suffix, etc). git is now a runtime
       dep of --sync-branches; checked at the top of the sync loop in
       main() so a missing binary fails loudly rather than silently
       rejecting every repo.

    2. P3: dm-github-fork-sync wraps github-org-fork with a per-source
       --exclude (Whonix .github + canary collisions). github-org-fork's
       parser stored only the LAST --exclude, so a user-supplied
       --exclude on dm-github-fork-sync would overwrite the per-source
       collision exclusion and reintroduce the .github / canary HTTP 422
       path the change was trying to avoid.

       Fix: github-org-fork accumulates multiple --include and --exclude
       values into arrays during parsing, then OR-combines them into a
       single grep -E regex via a small combine_alt helper. Each
       individual pattern is wrapped in (...) so alternation between
       user-supplied and wrapper-supplied filters is unambiguous even
       if one of them contains a bare '|'.

       Symmetrically fixed for --include even though no current caller
       relies on it; the surprising last-flag-wins behaviour was
       inconsistent for both.

    https://claude.ai/code/session_01U5dqsVj1msLQMiCemkuddP

commit 03aeaa4d363933fc9f6e08fc65638a04037c669b
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Sun May 3 22:38:09 2026 +0000

    github-org-fork: sanitize merged_commits before logging sync result

    Codex P2 review on PR #7: in sync_one's verbose-mode log notice line,
    merge_type was sanitized via ghorg_safe_print but merged_commits was
    interpolated raw. Both flow into the same display sink (a log call
    that ends up at the operator's terminal); both are API-derived bytes
    that a hostile or replayed GHORG_API endpoint can poison. Sanitize
    merged_commits via the same path.

    Note: 'commits=...' value is now also wrapped in single quotes so a
    non-numeric value (which the API shouldn't return, but might under
    hostile conditions) is visually delimited the same way merge_type is.

    https://claude.ai/code/session_01U5dqsVj1msLQMiCemkuddP

commit d26b86a7e1edd6d54162063ac9dc680f8e805439
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Sun May 3 21:43:32 2026 +0000

    github-org-fork: sync_one accepts hierarchical default branches

    Codex P2 review on PR #7: ghorg_validate_name with kind='repo' uses
    the repo-name allowlist (^[A-Za-z0-9._-]+$, max 100 chars), which
    disallows '/'. Branches like 'release/2026' or 'feature/foo' are
    valid git refs, so any mirror repo whose default branch is
    hierarchical was being silently skipped with a 'default branch
    invalid' warn instead of synced.

    Replace ghorg_validate_name with an inline allowlist tuned for git
    ref names: A-Za-z0-9._/- with a 256-char cap, plus the same
    arg-injection ('-'-prefix) and '..' rejections ghorg_validate_name
    applies. The branch name still flows safely into the request body
    (jq escapes) and into display (sanitized via ghorg_safe_print).

    https://claude.ai/code/session_01U5dqsVj1msLQMiCemkuddP

commit 556a13cf5250ab943d4935321346f2edda3e12f5
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Sun May 3 21:01:10 2026 +0000

    github-org-fork / dm-github-fork-sync / dm-github-token-test: --sync-branches, log, dedup

    Three changes layered on top of the merged dm-github-fork-sync rename
    + partial fix series:

    github-org-fork:

    - New --sync-branches flag. After fork-create + configure, fast-forward
      each target repo's default branch from upstream via
      POST /repos/{owner}/{repo}/merge-upstream. Without this, the mirror
      only ever has fork-time tips - upstream commits never propagate.

      Default branch is API-derived from /repos/{owner}/{repo}.default_branch
      (most are 'master', some 'main'); validated via ghorg_validate_name
      before placing in the request body or in display via printf.

      Response handling:
        200 - synced (.merge_type=fast-forward|merge|none); 'log notice'
              shows merge_type and merged_commits in --verbose.
        409 - upstream and fork have diverged in a way merge-upstream
              cannot fast-forward (someone pushed to mirror directly);
              'log warn', loop continues.
        422 - default branch missing on either side; 'log warn'.
        other HTTP - 'log warn', loop continues.
      Best-effort: failure on one repo never aborts the run.

    - All warn paths in sync_one go through 'log warn' (not 'printf
      "%s\n" "warn: ..." >&2'). Status output goes through 'log notice'.
      Aligns with the lib's existing log function usage.

    dm-github-fork-sync:

    - --sync-branches in POLICY_FLAGS. Re-running the wrapper periodically
      (cron, or before each release-build) keeps mirror branches current
      with upstream.

    - SOURCE_EXCLUDE_RE map for per-source exclusions. Whonix and Kicksecure
      both have '.github' (org-meta) and 'canary' (warrant canary). Forking
      both lands the second-arriving source on a name already taken by the
      first - GitHub returns HTTP 422. Process Kicksecure first (wins those
      names), then exclude '^(\.github|canary)$' on Whonix so the run
      completes without those two predictable collisions.

    - Section header printf calls switched to log notice for consistency
      with the rest of the script's output.

    dm-github-token-test:

    - Replace the inline /user logic with ghorg_authenticated_user from
      the lib. The helper already does GET /user + status check + .login
      extraction + ghorg_validate_name on the result. Reusing it
      eliminates ~10 lines of duplicate code and one less place to drift
      from the lib's auth contract.

    https://claude.ai/code/session_01U5dqsVj1msLQMiCemkuddP

