commit c069ca4a7c79cc4daf4e0aec59fd3ab7652956bc
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Fri May 1 11:09:00 2026 +0000

    dm-github-policy: 2FA messaging now reflects Nov 2024 GA behavior

    Per the Nov 2024 GA change (github.blog/changelog/2024-11-07-...),
    enabling org 2FA enforcement no longer REMOVES non-compliant
    members - they keep membership but are blocked from org resources
    until they enroll. Three places had the outdated wording:

      * --apply step 4b skip message: refers to the new behavior plus
        the platform-wide 2FA mandate that GitHub is rolling out, which
        means the org-level toggle just front-runs the inevitable.
      * --audit "members lacking 2FA" header: was "would be removed by
        enforcement", now "would lose org access until they enroll".
      * audit_org_state header comment: was "two changes most likely
        to surprise" (Allowed-Actions tightening AND member removal);
        drops the member-removal half.

    Also confirmed via the OpenAPI spec that there is still no REST
    setter for two_factor_requirement_enabled (it remains read-only
    on GET /orgs/{org}; not in PATCH /orgs/{org} request schema). So
    this stays a UI-only step from --apply's perspective. The skip
    message + UI URL is unchanged.

    AI-Assisted

