commit 29cdc3beab923cf7fda7e9a32ac75a129af88649
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Fri May 1 10:14:04 2026 +0000

    remove AI-tell comments (style/refactor meta narration)

    Strip comments that document the SHAPE of the code or the history of
    how it got there, rather than non-obvious behaviour or hidden
    constraints. The exact category the user flagged:

      * "Trap target / Standalone function ... so the trap is auditable"
        headers above each cleanup function. The fact that the function
        is named and called from `trap NAME SIG` is self-evident.
        Removed in github-org-lib.bsh, dm-github-policy,
        ci/probe-live-unauth.sh, ci/tests/test_rate_limit_retry.sh.

    Other AI-tell categories found and trimmed:

      * Style/refactor justifications: "Standalone function (not an
        inline command string)", "belt and braces", "Defense-in-depth
        against hostile origins", "Reads better, surfaces intermediate
        names", "even though no operand is an option here". Either
        deleted outright or compressed to one line of substantive
        rationale.

      * Self-referential refactor history: "Avoids the previous
        \"comm -23 <(printf ...) <(printf ...)\" form, which ran printf
        in two process substitutions whose exit codes errexit could
        not see"; "Replaced with a small helper"; "Same set-
        intersection idea, in pure bash". Belongs in commit messages
        and PR descriptions, not the source.

      * Verbose threat-model exposition: trimmed the THREAT MODEL block
        in github-org-lib.bsh from a 56-line essay to ~15 lines. The
        actual policy (validate at identifier sinks, sanitize at
        display sinks) is what matters; the why-this-policy paragraphs
        were re-stating the obvious for an AI reviewer.

      * Per-tunable doc bloat: each GHORG_MAX_* knob had a multi-line
        paragraph. Compressed each to one short comment plus the
        assignment.

      * Step-by-step "## Verified against the OpenAPI spec ..." in
        apply_org_policy step 4: removed; the kept body fields ARE
        the verified set, listing them again as "present:" is noise.

      * "## TODO: replace with real API calls when GitHub publishes
        stable REST endpoints" + "## Sample of what would be set if a
        stable REST surface existed" with a commented-out body block.
        Both removed: the skip+UI URL is the actual behaviour; a
        speculative future API does not need to be carried as dead
        JSON in the source.

      * "## install_line is jq-extracted from an untrusted body
        (.app_slug + .id concatenated). Sanitize before display." -
        redundant with the variable name `safe_install_line` and the
        call to ghorg_safe_print on the next line.

      * Comment paraphrasing the function name: "## Records a SKIP
        event. Used by apply_org_policy for settings that have no
        REST API". Removed; record_skip() { api_record skip; } speaks
        for itself.

    What is KEPT (still valuable, not AI-tell):
      * Real invariants and gotchas: PIPE_BUF atomicity for the
        counter tempfile; @{u} ref ambiguity protection; the leading-
        dot exception for .github / .gitignore validation.
      * External-system references: HTTP 409 on selected-actions when
        allowed_actions != "selected"; OpenAPI spec field availability
        notes where they shape the body.
      * Args/returns docstrings for non-trivial functions.

    AI-Assisted

