commit ec4d43a40262d960f858e842f284fba31bc6ebc7
Author: Claude <noreply@anthropic.com>
Date:   Fri May 1 10:01:58 2026 +0000

    github-org-fork: pure-bash set diff/intersect; lib: capture jq output

    Two coordinated changes to remove subshell-via-process-substitution
    patterns whose exit codes were invisible to errexit + pipefail.

      * github-org-fork main(): the previous "missing" / "to_configure"
        set computations used "comm -23 <(printf ...) <(printf ...)" and
        "comm -12 <(printf ...) <(printf ...)". The two process subs
        each ran in their own subshell whose failure could not surface
        to the parent; a printf failure inside one would silently feed
        comm an empty stream, making the operator think a source-only
        or shared-set was empty.

        Replaced with a small helper, fork_main_build_repo_set, that
        populates a passed-by-name associative array from a newline-
        separated string. main() builds target_set once, computes
        "missing" by absence-from-set, and "to_configure" by
        presence-in-set. Both are local arrays. No external comm, no
        process subs.

        The "${target_set[${repo_name}]:-}" subscript needs the :- form
        because bash's set -o nounset triggers on associative-array
        subscripts of unset keys; documented inline as a "the absence
        IS the signal" case rather than a default-hides-a-bug case.

        Variable names use repo_name throughout (the previous "$r" was
        rejected as too short).

      * github-org-lib.bsh ghorg_list_repos: the "while IFS= read -r ...
        done < <(printf | jq)" loop pre-captures jq output into a
        names_text string first, then iterates with "<<< \${names_text}".
        Same rationale: with errexit + pipefail + inherit_errexit, the
        "$( ... )" capture surfaces a jq failure; the prior "<( ... )"
        form silently treated jq failure as an empty page.

    Note on the remaining "<()" cases (not changed in this commit, kept
    as-is by judgment):

      - github-org-push main(): "find ... -print0 | sort --zero-terminated"
        feeds NUL-delimited candidate dirs into a "read -d ''" loop. NUL-
        safe pre-capture via "$( ... )" is not possible (bash strings
        can not contain NUL). A tempfile-based variant is the
        error-aware alternative; deferred for now since "find" rarely
        exits non-zero in practice (it warns on per-entry permission
        failures rather than aborting).

      - ci/tests/test_shellcheck_clean.sh: same pattern as above for
        enumerating test files. Same trade-off, same deferral. If the
        enumerator silently fails, we run shellcheck on zero files and
        the test passes - a quiet false negative. Worth a follow-up
        tempfile fix.

    AI-Assisted

